    "displayTerm": "Flight Attendant Fainted",
    "term": "flight attendant fainted",
    "slug": "flight-attendant-fainted",
    "category": "Crew",
    "meaningEn": "Flight Attendant Fainted describes a cabin crew member who has lost consciousness and is unable to continue cabin duties, requiring first aid, possible crew reassignment, and ATC notification if medical assistance or priority handling is needed.",
    "meaningPt": "Comissário(a) desmaiado(a) / Flight Attendant Fainted.\n\nSituação em que um membro da tripulação de cabine perde a consciência e não pode continuar as funções de cabine, exigindo primeiros socorros, possível redistribuição de tarefas e notificação ao controle se for necessária assistência médica ou prioridade.",
    "whenUsed": "When a flight attendant faints, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger Pan Pan, say souls on board and assistance required.",
    "sayPhrase": "Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, flight attendant fainted, request medical assistance on landing.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Why must pilots be able to say \"flight attendant fainted\" clearly even if they fly helicopters without cabin crew?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Because ICAO speaking tests use standard multi-crew cabin scenarios. The phrase shows I can report a crew medical problem and request assistance. In helicopter operations without cabin crew, I apply the same structure to any crew member or helper who becomes unconscious.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Flight Attendant Fainted — a cabin crew medical event in which a flight attendant loses consciousness and can no longer perform cabin duties.\n\nThis concept appears in ICAO exam English because many Part 2 and Part 3 scenarios assume airliner cabin crew. You must know the standard phraseology even when your daily aircraft is an H130.\n\nFor H130 Brazilian operations, there is often no flight attendant at all. Treat this lesson as exam language plus transferable CRM: any crew member or passenger helper who becomes unconscious reduces your support capacity. The radio message still centers on medical problem, crew status, and assistance required.\n\nUnderstanding how to communicate a flight attendant fainted event in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3.",
    "captainTeaching": "Examiners want two things: correct medical English and a clear operational request.\n\n\"Flight attendant fainted\" is specific. It tells ATC the problem is crew medical, not a random passenger story.\n\nThen say what you need: medical assistance, priority landing, or both.\n\nIn airline CRM, remaining attendants cover doors and cabin. In the H130 world, there may be nobody left to cover anything. That raises the urgency of a clean landing and medical meet.\n\nDo not confuse this with pilot incapacitation. A fainted attendant is serious; an incapacitated flying pilot is immediately critical. Use the right label.\n\nLearn the airliner phrase. Apply the helicopter judgment.",
    "operationalContext": "ICAO exam scenario: you are the captain of a multi-crew aircraft when cabin reports a flight attendant has fainted in the aisle.\n\nYou confirm another attendant is providing care and the cabin remains secure.\n\nYou transmit:\n\nPan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, medical problem on board, flight attendant unconscious, request medical assistance on landing.\n\nH130 note: if your second pilot or a passenger helper collapses instead, the structure is the same — medical problem, who is affected, what you need from ATC.",
    "sayItCoach": "Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, flight attendant fainted, request medical assistance on landing.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Because ICAO speaking tests use standard multi-crew cabin scenarios. The phrase shows I can report a crew medical problem and request assistance. In helicopter operations without cabin crew, I apply the same structure to any crew member or helper who becomes unconscious.",
    "memoryTrick": "**CREW** — **C**all it cabin crew clearly, **R**equest medical help, **E**valuate remaining cabin capability, **W**atch that this is not pilot incapacitation.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When a flight attendant faints, the crew should:\n\nFlight Attendant Fainted communication commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger Pan Pan, say souls on board and assistance required.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, medical services will meet you on arrival.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, cleared to land, ambulance standing by.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, confirm cabin crew still able to perform duties.",
      "Control: ANAC123, priority approach available if required."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, flight attendant fainted, request medical assistance on landing.",
      "ANAC123, medical problem on board, cabin crew member unconscious.",
      "ANAC123, flight attendant regained consciousness, still request medical meet on arrival.",
      "ANAC123, requesting priority landing, crew medical problem.",
      "ANAC123, souls on board one two eight, one cabin crew unconscious."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Saying \"the stewardess fell\" or informal slang on frequency.  \n  ✔ Say flight attendant fainted or cabin crew member unconscious.\n\n- ❌ Reporting the event without requesting assistance.  \n  ✔ Add request medical assistance on landing.\n\n- ❌ Treating it automatically as Mayday.  \n  ✔ Use Pan Pan for urgency unless life is immediately threatened and distress is required.\n\n- ❌ Ignoring cabin safety after the faint.  \n  ✔ Confirm remaining crew can still manage passengers and exits.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** Flight Attendant Fainted, Request Medical Assistance\n\n**Pronunciation:** FLITE uh-TEN-dant FAYNT-ed, reh-KWEST MED-ih-kul uh-SIS-tans\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Attendant → uh-TEN-dant (stress on second)\n- Fainted → FAYNT-ed\n- Medical → MED-ih-kul\n- Assistance → uh-SIS-tans\n\nPractice:\n\nFlight attendant fainted... request medical assistance.\n\nTogether:\n\nPan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, flight attendant fainted, request medical assistance on landing.",
