    "id": "0332",
    "displayTerm": "Unruly Passenger",
    "term": "unruly passenger",
    "slug": "unruly-passenger",
    "category": "Passenger",
    "meaningEn": "Unruly Passenger describes a passenger who fails to comply with safety instructions or behaves in a disruptive, aggressive, or threatening manner that may compromise flight safety and require crew action and ATC coordination for assistance on arrival.",
    "meaningPt": "Passageiro indisciplinado / Unruly Passenger.\n\nPassageiro que não cumpre instruções de segurança ou se comporta de forma disruptiva, agressiva ou ameaçadora, podendo comprometer a segurança do voo e exigir ação da tripulação e coordenação com o controle para assistência na chegada.",
    "whenUsed": "When dealing with an unruly passenger, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger Pan Pan, say nature of problem and souls on board.",
    "sayPhrase": "Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, unruly passenger on board, request priority landing and security assistance.",
    "icaoQuestion": "What should you tell ATC when a passenger becomes aggressive and may threaten flight safety?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would declare Pan Pan if safety is threatened, state that there is an unruly passenger or security problem on board, and request priority landing and security or police assistance on arrival. I would keep control of the aircraft and prevent the passenger from interfering with the flight controls.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Unruly Passenger — a passenger whose behavior threatens safety, order, or crew ability to operate the flight, including aggression, refusal to follow safety instructions, or interference with the crew.\n\nUnruly Passenger is High priority because behavior problems can escalate into assault, cockpit interference, or unsafe cabin conditions. ICAO exams expect clear English: unruly passenger, security problem, request assistance on landing, and priority if the situation threatens safety.\n\nFor H130 operations, the cabin is small and there is usually no cabin crew. An unruly passenger is closer to the controls. Early firm management and early ATC notification matter more, not less.\n\nUnderstanding how to communicate an unruly passenger event in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3.",
    "captainTeaching": "Unruly is the standard ICAO exam word. Use it.\n\nSource materials may say passenger fighting, misbehavior, or misconduct. On frequency, unruly passenger or security problem is cleaner.\n\nYour goal is not to win an argument. Your goal is a safe aircraft and a secure landing.\n\nIn airliners, cabin crew manage the cabin. In the H130, proximity is the danger. One meter from an aggressive passenger to the cyclic is too close. Divert sooner than pride allows.\n\nTell ATC what you need: security, police, priority. Do not narrate every insult on frequency.\n\nFirm. Short. Early.",
    "operationalContext": "You are approaching Guarulhos in the H130 with four passengers.\n\nOne passenger becomes aggressive, refuses to remain seated, and tries to move toward the front.\n\nYou keep control, order the passenger to sit, and have another passenger block the aisle area.\n\nYou transmit:\n\nPan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, unruly passenger on board, request priority landing and security assistance.\n\nApproach gives you priority. Police meet the aircraft after landing. The situation never reached the controls because you acted early on frequency and in the cabin.",
    "sayItCoach": "Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, unruly passenger on board, request priority landing and security assistance.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would declare Pan Pan if safety is threatened, state that there is an unruly passenger or security problem on board, and request priority landing and security or police assistance on arrival. I would keep control of the aircraft and prevent the passenger from interfering with the flight controls.",
    "memoryTrick": "**RULE** — **R**eport unruly early, **U**se Pan Pan if safety threatened, **L**ock focus on flying, **E**scort request = security on arrival.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When dealing with an unruly passenger, the crew should:\n\nUnruly Passenger communication commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger Pan Pan, say nature of problem and souls on board.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, priority approach, security alerted.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, cleared to land, police will meet you on the apron.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, confirm passenger under control.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, taxi to isolated stand, security standing by."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, unruly passenger on board, request priority landing and security assistance.",
      "ANAC123, security problem on board, passenger aggressive, request police on arrival.",
      "ANAC123, unruly passenger restrained, request security meet aircraft.",
      "ANAC123, passenger interfering with crew, request immediate landing.",
      "ANAC123, souls on board five, unruly passenger, security required."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Saying only \"passenger crazy\" or slang.  \n  ✔ Say unruly passenger or security problem on board.\n\n- ❌ Waiting until the passenger reaches the controls before calling ATC.  \n  ✔ Notify early and request security assistance.\n\n- ❌ Leaving the controls to restrain the passenger in single-pilot ops.  \n  ✔ Fly first; use other passengers if restraint is unavoidable and legal.\n\n- ❌ Forgetting to request police on arrival.  \n  ✔ Always request security or police meet the aircraft when behavior is aggressive.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** Unruly Passenger On Board, Request Security Assistance\n\n**Pronunciation:** un-ROO-lee PASS-en-jer on BOARD, reh-KWEST suh-KYOOR-ih-tee uh-SIS-tans\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Unruly → un-ROO-lee (stress on second)\n- Passenger → PASS-en-jer\n- Security → suh-KYOOR-ih-tee\n\nPractice:\n\nUnruly passenger on board...\n\nTogether:\n\nPan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, unruly passenger on board, request priority landing and security assistance.",
