    "displayTerm": "Diabetic Emergency",
    "term": "diabetic emergency",
    "slug": "diabetic-emergency",
    "category": "Passenger",
    "meaningEn": "Diabetic Emergency is a medical crisis related to diabetes — typically hypoglycemia (low blood sugar) or severe hyperglycemia — that may cause altered consciousness, sweating, confusion, seizure, or unconsciousness and requires medical assistance.",
    "meaningPt": "Emergência diabética / Diabetic Emergency.\n\nCrise médica relacionada ao diabetes — tipicamente hipoglicemia (açúcar baixo no sangue) ou hiperglicemia grave — que pode causar alteração de consciência, sudorese, confusão, convulsão ou inconsciência e exige assistência médica.",
    "whenUsed": "When a diabetic emergency occurs, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger Pan Pan, say if passenger is conscious.",
    "sayPhrase": "Pan Pan Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, diabetic emergency on board, passenger unconscious, request priority landing and medical assistance.",
    "icaoQuestion": "A diabetic passenger becomes unconscious. What do you tell ATC?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would declare Pan Pan, report diabetic emergency on board with passenger unconscious, request priority landing at the nearest suitable airport, and request medical assistance. I would provide souls on board when asked and update ATC if the passenger starts seizing or recovers consciousness.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Diabetic Emergency — a passenger medical event involving low or high blood sugar that may cause confusion, unconsciousness, or seizures and require priority landing and medical assistance.\n\nICAO exams expect operational English: diabetic emergency, passenger unconscious, request medical assistance — not a lecture on insulin types.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations under ICAO Delta academy training in Brazil, crews may encounter diabetic events on charter or passenger flights. Cabin treatment options are limited. If the passenger becomes unconscious or seizing, diversion and clear ATC communication are the professional response.\n\nMaster the phraseology so urgency, diversion, and ground medical support are coordinated without delay.",
    "captainTeaching": "Diabetic emergency is common enough to train — and easy to mishandle on the radio.\n\nDo not say \"açúcar\" and hope ATC understands. Say diabetic emergency, then the state: unconscious, confused, seizure.\n\nBrazilian pilots may say \"crise de diabetes\" or \"hipoglicemia.\" Prefer diabetic emergency on board for ICAO English, then the observable condition.\n\nIf cabin gives sugar and the passenger improves, still request medical assistance after a serious event. Improvement in flight is not a full medical clearance.\n\nIn the H130, one unresponsive passenger fills the cabin with workload. Divert early. Keep the frequency clean. Fly the approach.\n\nPan Pan is normally correct. Escalate if the situation becomes immediately life-threatening and you need absolute priority.",
    "operationalContext": "You are en route from Belo Horizonte toward the coast when cabin reports a known diabetic passenger who is confused and sweating, then becomes unresponsive.\n\nYou declare Pan Pan, divert to the nearest suitable airport, and request medical assistance.\n\nApproach clears traffic and alerts ambulances. You land. Medical services meet the aircraft. The passenger is transferred.\n\nYou report condition changes only when they matter: unconscious, improving, seizing.",
    "sayItCoach": "Pan Pan Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, diabetic emergency on board, passenger unconscious, request priority landing.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would declare Pan Pan, report diabetic emergency on board with passenger unconscious, request priority landing at the nearest suitable airport, and request medical assistance. I would provide souls on board when asked and update ATC if the passenger starts seizing or recovers consciousness.",
    "memoryTrick": "**SUGAR** — **S**tate diabetic emergency, **U**pdate conscious status, **G**et priority landing, **A**sk for medical assistance, **R**eroute/divert if unresponsive.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When a diabetic emergency occurs, the crew should:\n\nDiabetic emergency reporting commonly includes:",
