    "icaoQuestion": "What is a first officer, and what should you say if the captain becomes incapacitated?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "The first officer is the co-pilot and second-in-command. If the captain becomes incapacitated, I would take control of the aircraft and declare Mayday, reporting captain incapacitated, first officer assuming control, and request vectors to the nearest suitable airport and medical assistance.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers First Officer — the co-pilot on a multi-crew flight deck, second-in-command to the captain, sharing handling, monitoring, and radio duties under the operator's SOP and CRM principles.\n\nICAO Part 1 and Part 2 expect accurate crew titles: captain, first officer, pilot flying, pilot monitoring. Controllers may hear either pilot on frequency; the callsign remains the aircraft callsign.\n\nFor H130 ICAO Delta academy training in Brazil, many operations are single-pilot. Two-crew training, check flights, and exam scenarios still require correct first officer language — including assuming control after captain incapacitation.\n\nMaster: first officer, co-pilot, assuming control, pilot monitoring.",
    "captainTeaching": "First officer means second-in-command — not \"assistant who only talks on the radio.\"\n\nIn modern CRM, the first officer challenges, monitors, and flies when assigned. Authority gradient must not silence a safety call.\n\nBrazilian Portuguese: primeiro oficial or copiloto. Prefer first officer in ICAO English.\n\nIf you take over after incapacitation, say first officer assuming control. Controllers and examiners need that clarity.\n\nIn single-pilot H130 ops, you are not a first officer — do not invent multi-crew structure. When the scenario is two-crew, use the titles correctly.",
    "operationalContext": "Two-crew H130 training flight toward Navegantes. The first officer is pilot monitoring, handling radios.\n\nThe captain briefs the approach. The first officer reads back clearances and monitors altitudes.\n\nIf the captain becomes unresponsive, the first officer takes control and declares Mayday: captain incapacitated, first officer assuming control.\n\nDaily Brazilian single-pilot H130 flights may have no first officer — the exam still tests the role.",
