    "meaningEn": "Captain is the pilot-in-command of the aircraft, responsible for the safe conduct of the flight, crew coordination, and final operational decisions in accordance with regulations and company procedures.",
    "meaningPt": "Comandante / Captain / Pilot-in-Command.\n\nPiloto em comando da aeronave, responsável pela condução segura do voo, pela coordenação da tripulação e pelas decisões operacionais finais de acordo com os regulamentos e os procedimentos da empresa.",
    "whenUsed": "When acting as captain, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger diversion, say intentions.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, diverting Florianópolis due to weather, request vectors.",
    "icaoQuestion": "What is the captain responsible for, and how might that appear in ATC communication?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "The captain is the pilot-in-command, responsible for the safety of the flight and final operational decisions. That appears in ATC communication as clear intentions: diverting, unable to comply with a request for alternative clearance, declaring Mayday or Pan Pan, or requesting priority landing when required.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Captain — the pilot-in-command, legally responsible for the operation and safety of the aircraft, final authority on board, and the standard ICAO title for the crew member in command.\n\nPart 1 vocabulary and Part 2 operational English require precise use of captain, pilot-in-command, and command authority — especially in briefings, incapacitation scenarios, and decision announcements.\n\nFor H130 ICAO Delta academy operations in Brazil, the captain role often equals the single pilot-in-command. In two-crew operations, the captain remains PIC even when the first officer is pilot flying.\n\nMaster: captain, pilot-in-command, final authority, command decision.",
    "captainTeaching": "Captain means you own the outcome.\n\nCRM does not remove command — it improves it. Listen to the first officer. Then decide.\n\nBrazilian Portuguese: comandante. ICAO English: captain or pilot-in-command.\n\nDo not confuse captain with check pilot or relief pilot. Those are different roles that may sit in the flight deck without replacing PIC authority unless formally transferred under procedure.\n\nIn single-pilot H130 Brazilian operations, you are the captain every flight. Speak decisions clearly to ATC: diverting, unable, declaring emergency, going around.\n\nAuthority without clarity creates confusion. Clarity without authority creates drift. Use both.",
    "operationalContext": "You are captain of an H130 flight from Congonhas toward the coast. Weather ahead deteriorates.\n\nYou decide to divert. You tell ATC you are diverting due to weather and request vectors.\n\nThe decision is yours as PIC. The radio call is standard and calm.\n\nIn two-crew airline scenarios, you may be pilot monitoring while still remaining captain. Role of flying and role of command are not always the same seat task — command remains with the captain.",
    "sayItCoach": "Diverting due to weather, request vectors to alternate.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "The captain is the pilot-in-command, responsible for the safety of the flight and final operational decisions. That appears in ATC communication as clear intentions: diverting, unable to comply with a request for alternative clearance, declaring Mayday or Pan Pan, or requesting priority landing when required.",
    "memoryTrick": "**PIC** — **P**lan and brief, **I**ntentions to ATC clear, **C**ommand decision owned end-to-end.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When acting as captain, the pilot should:\n\nCaptain-related communications commonly include:",
