    "icaoQuestion": "What is a relief pilot?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "A relief pilot is a qualified pilot who temporarily takes a flight deck duty position to relieve the captain or first officer during long operations, supporting fatigue management. Control is transferred with clear briefings and callouts, and command authority follows the operator's procedures.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Relief Pilot — a qualified pilot carried to relieve the captain or first officer from flight deck duty during long-range or extended operations, supporting fatigue management and controlled transfer of control.\n\nICAO Part 1 vocabulary distinguishes relief pilot from captain, first officer, and check pilot. Controllers may never hear the words \"relief pilot,\" but examiners will. Operational English must describe controlled seat changes and who is flying.\n\nFor H130 ICAO Delta academy training in Brazil, true cruise-relief operations are uncommon on short helicopter sectors — yet the term appears in multi-crew airline English and must be answered correctly.\n\nMaster: relief pilot, controlled rest, transfer of control, fatigue management.",
    "captainTeaching": "Relief pilot is about fatigue and continuity — not a third captain by default.\n\nUse the term correctly on exams. Describe a controlled transfer of control. Emphasize briefings and callouts.\n\nBrazilian Portuguese: piloto de alívio. Prefer relief pilot in ICAO English.\n\nDo not confuse relief pilot with check pilot. A check pilot evaluates. A relief pilot replaces a duty period.\n\nIn H130 ops, manage fatigue with duty limits and realistic scheduling instead of inventing cruise-relief procedures the operation does not use. Still know the airline term.\n\nIf seat changes happen, freeze non-essential tasks. Fly. Confirm. Then talk.",
    "operationalContext": "Long-haul airliner exam scenario: mid-Atlantic cruise, the relief pilot enters the flight deck to relieve the first officer.\n\nControl is transferred with standard callouts. Radios remain monitored. ATC hears only normal position reports from the callsign.\n\nIn H130 Brazilian short-sector flying, you may never roster a relief pilot. If asked what a relief pilot is, answer with fatigue-relief and temporary duty assumption — not \"extra passenger.\"",
    "sayItCoach": "Relief pilot taking the seat, control transferred, clearance unchanged.",
