    "displayTerm": "Brace Position",
    "term": "brace position",
    "slug": "brace-position",
    "category": "Emergency",
    "meaningEn": "Brace Position is the protective seating posture adopted by crew and passengers immediately before an expected impact, forced landing, or ditching, designed to reduce injury from deceleration and debris, commanded by the crew when landing is imminent and survival depends on correct body position.",
    "meaningPt": "Posição de proteção / Brace Position.\n\nPostura protetora adotada pela tripulação e passageiros imediatamente antes de um impacto esperado, pouso forçado ou amerissagem, destinada a reduzir lesões por desaceleração e debris, comandada pela tripulação quando o pouso é iminente e a sobrevivência depende da posição corporal correta.",
    "whenUsed": "When brace position is required, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger Mayday, say souls on board and position.",
    "sayPhrase": "Mayday Mayday Mayday, Approach, ANAC123, engine failure, forced landing imminent, two miles south of Navegantes.",
    "icaoQuestion": "What is brace position, and what do you tell ATC before a forced landing?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Brace position is the protective posture occupants take before an expected impact. I would command brace to the cabin when landing is imminent. To ATC I would declare Mayday, state the emergency — for example engine failure — report forced landing imminent with position, and request rescue. After landing I would report landing complete and whether we are evacuating.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Brace Position — the protective body posture commanded before an imminent impact, ditching, or crash landing so occupants reduce injury risk during the landing sequence.\n\nBrace position is cabin and cockpit language as much as radio language. On the ICAO exam you must explain it; in operations you must command it and, when needed, tell ATC that a forced landing or ditching is imminent.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations under ICAO Delta academy training in Brazil, brace applies before autorotation touchdown, forced landing, or ditching — with rotor and door considerations, not airliner slide choreography.\n\nUnderstanding brace position in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Brace position saves bodies. Mayday saves the response.\n\nDo not confuse the two audiences. Occupants hear brace. ATC hears forced landing or ditching imminent.\n\nBrazilian crews sometimes translate awkwardly — \"posição de impacto\" on frequency. Keep brace in the cabin. On the radio: Mayday, malfunction, landing now, position, souls.\n\nIn the H130, brief early when the autorotation allows. Command late and loud when the ground is close. After landing, evacuate clear of rotors and fire risk.\n\nExaminers want you to know what brace means and when you command it — then switch to clean distress phraseology for ATC.",
    "operationalContext": "En route along the Santa Catarina coast in the H130, engine failure forces an autorotation toward a clear field near Navegantes.\n\nYou declare Mayday, state engine failure and forced landing. With seconds left, you command brace to occupants. After touchdown you shut down, open doors, and get clear.\n\nTower and Approach already have rescue moving because the Mayday was early and clear — not because you described brace technique on the radio.",
    "sayItCoach": "Mayday Mayday Mayday, ANAC123, forced landing imminent, request rescue.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Brace position is the protective posture occupants take before an expected impact. I would command brace to the cabin when landing is imminent. To ATC I would declare Mayday, state the emergency — for example engine failure — report forced landing imminent with position, and request rescue. After landing I would report landing complete and whether we are evacuating.",
    "memoryTrick": "**BRACE** — **B**rief early if time, **R**adio Mayday first to ATC, **A**ttitude and site selection, **C**ommand brace to occupants, **E**vacuate clear after touchdown.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When brace position is required, the crew should:\n\nBrace-related reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger Mayday, say souls on board and position.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, emergency services alerted, report landing complete if able.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, runway vacated for you if able to reach field, wind calm.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, SAR and fire services rolling, say if ditching or landing on field.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, confirm all souls clear after landing."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "Mayday Mayday Mayday, Approach, ANAC123, engine failure, forced landing imminent, two miles south of Navegantes.",
      "ANAC123, souls on board four, forced landing on open field, request rescue.",
      "ANAC123, ditching imminent, request SAR.",
      "ANAC123, landing complete, evacuating, request fire services.",
      "ANAC123, all souls clear of aircraft, awaiting rescue."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Explaining brace technique to ATC on a congested frequency.  \n  ✔ Cabin gets the brace command; ATC gets Mayday and landing intention.\n\n- ❌ Delaying Mayday until after the brace call.  \n  ✔ Declare early so rescue is already moving.\n\n- ❌ Forgetting souls and position in the distress call.  \n  ✔ Include position and souls when able.\n\n- ❌ Using only Portuguese cabin commands in an ICAO oral answer.  \n  ✔ Explain brace in English; demonstrate standard Mayday phraseology.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** Brace Brace Brace — Forced Landing Imminent\n\n**Pronunciation:** BRAYSS BRAYSS BRAYSS — FORST LAND-ing IH-muh-nunt\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Brace → BRAYSS\n- Forced → FORST\n- Landing → LAND-ing\n- Imminent → IH-muh-nunt\n\nPractice:\n\nBrace brace brace... forced landing imminent...\n\nTogether:\n\nMayday Mayday Mayday, ANAC123, forced landing imminent, request rescue.",
