    "catalogId": "0360",
    "id": "0360",
    "displayTerm": "Sandstorm",
    "term": "sandstorm",
    "slug": "sandstorm",
    "category": "Weather",
    "meaningEn": "Sandstorm is a meteorological event in which strong winds lift sand particles into the atmosphere, causing very low visibility and abrasive conditions hazardous to flight, typically requiring avoidance, delay, or diversion rather than penetration of the storm.",
    "meaningPt": "Tempestade de areia / Sandstorm.\n\nEvento meteorológico em que ventos fortes levantam partículas de areia na atmosfera, causando visibilidade muito baixa e condições abrasivas perigosas ao voo, tipicamente exigindo desvio, atraso ou espera em vez de penetração na tempestade.",
    "whenUsed": "When a sandstorm affects operations, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, sandstorm over the field, visibility five hundred meters, advise intentions.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, sandstorm over the field, request divert.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Destination is reporting a sandstorm with very low visibility. What do you tell ATC?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would report unable to approach due to sandstorm and request hold if improvement is expected soon, or request diversion to a suitable alternate. I would not attempt a visual approach into the sandstorm.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Sandstorm — a strong wind event that lifts sand into the air, severely reducing visibility and creating abrasive conditions for engines, blades, and windscreens, often requiring delay, diversion, or holding until the storm passes.\n\nSandstorms are high-impact low-visibility events. ICAO English must state sandstorm, visibility if known, and clear intentions: hold, divert, or unable approach.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations under ICAO Delta academy training in Brazil, true desert sandstorms are uncommon in most training areas, but the concept appears in ICAO exams and in operations over dry interior regions and international deployments. Treat it as a visibility and engine-ingestion hazard.\n\nUnderstanding sandstorm phraseology is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Sandstorm is a wall you do not fly through for schedule.\n\nVisibility dies. Engines ingest. Blades erode.\n\nBrazilian students may never see a classic desert sandstorm in São Paulo — still master the English. Examiners use it.\n\nIn the H130, low-level flight into blowing sand is a trap. Divert or wait. Say sandstorm, not only \"baixa visibilidade,\" so the hazard type is clear.\n\nHigh priority because penetration decisions are often irreversible at low altitude.",
    "operationalContext": "Diverting toward an interior Brazilian alternate in the H130, METAR shows visibility dropping in a sandstorm. Approach advises sandstorm over the field, visibility five hundred meters.\n\nYou request diversion to a coastal alternate still reporting VMC. You do not attempt a visual approach into the sand wall. After landing at the alternate you report the diversion reason as sandstorm at destination.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, sandstorm over the field, unable approach, request divert.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would report unable to approach due to sandstorm and request hold if improvement is expected soon, or request diversion to a suitable alternate. I would not attempt a visual approach into the sandstorm.",
    "memoryTrick": "**SAND** — **S**top the approach idea, **A**sk for hold or divert, **N**ame it sandstorm, **D**o not penetrate for schedule.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When a sandstorm affects operations, the crew should:\n\nSandstorm reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, sandstorm over the field, visibility five hundred meters, advise intentions.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, runway visual range below minima, expect delay.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, divert approved, contact Center on...",
      "Center: ANAC123, sandstorm reported along your route, advise.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, sandstorm moving east, expect improvement in one hour."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, sandstorm over the field, request divert.",
      "ANAC123, unable approach due to sandstorm, request hold.",
      "ANAC123, diverting for sandstorm, request routing to alternate.",
      "ANAC123, sandstorm ahead, request weather deviation.",
      "ANAC123, field not in sight, sandstorm, request vectors for delay."
    ],
