    "category": "Weather",
    "meaningEn": "Dust Storm is a meteorological condition in which strong winds raise fine dust particles into the atmosphere over a large area, causing widespread low visibility and hazardous flight conditions that normally require delay, holding, or diversion rather than flight into the dust.",
    "meaningPt": "Tempestade de poeira / Dust Storm.\n\nCondição meteorológica em que ventos fortes levantam finas partículas de poeira na atmosfera sobre uma área ampla, causando baixa visibilidade generalizada e condições de voo perigosas que normalmente exigem atraso, espera ou desvio em vez de voo para dentro da poeira.",
    "whenUsed": "When a dust storm is present or forecast, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, dust storm over the field, visibility eight hundred meters, advise intentions.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, dust storm over the field, request divert.",
    "icaoQuestion": "You encounter a dust storm that obscures your destination. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would report dust storm over the field or ahead, state that I am unable to continue the visual approach, and request hold if a short delay will help or diversion to a suitable alternate. I would not enter the dust storm to find the runway.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Dust Storm — strong winds lifting fine dust into the air over a wide area, reducing visibility significantly and creating operational hazards similar to sandstorms, often with dust carried to higher altitudes.\n\nDust storms can arrive as a wall of reduced visibility. Crews must report dust storm, state intentions, and avoid low-visibility penetration — especially in helicopters operating near the surface.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations under ICAO Delta academy training in Brazil, dry-season dust and blowing dust occur over interior plateaus and unpaved areas. ICAO exams also use dust storm as standard meteorological vocabulary.\n\nUnderstanding dust storm phraseology is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Dust storm is sandstorm's wider, finer cousin.\n\nSame decision: do not penetrate for schedule.\n\nBrazilian interior dry season can produce blowing dust that surprises VFR helicopters. If the horizon turns brown, turn around or climb with ATC — do not press into the wall.\n\nSay dust storm so meteorology and ATC log the correct phenomenon. \"Não dá para ver\" is not enough for a professional PIREP.",
    "operationalContext": "Inbound to an interior field in the H130, you see a brown wall ahead. Approach confirms dust storm over the field, visibility eight hundred meters.\n\nYou request diversion to an alternate east of the dust. Center clears the divert. You remain in VMC, land clean, and file the weather reason as dust storm at destination.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, dust storm over the field, unable approach, request divert.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would report dust storm over the field or ahead, state that I am unable to continue the visual approach, and request hold if a short delay will help or diversion to a suitable alternate. I would not enter the dust storm to find the runway.",
    "memoryTrick": "**DUST** — **D**ivert or hold, **U**nable visual if obscured, **S**ay dust storm clearly, **T**urn away from the brown wall.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When a dust storm is present or forecast, the crew should:\n\nDust storm reporting commonly includes:",
