    "catalogId": "0366",
    "id": "0366",
    "displayTerm": "Rime Ice",
    "term": "rime ice",
    "slug": "rime-ice",
    "category": "Weather",
    "meaningEn": "Rime Ice is a milky, opaque, granular ice deposit formed when small supercooled droplets freeze almost instantly on impact with an aircraft surface, usually in stratiform cloud at sub-freezing temperatures, producing a rough texture that disrupts airflow and increases drag and weight.",
    "meaningPt": "Gelo rime / Rime Ice.\n\nDepósito de gelo leitoso, opaco e granular formado quando pequenas gotículas super-resfriadas congelam quase instantaneamente ao impactar a superfície da aeronave, geralmente em nuvem estratiforme em temperaturas abaixo de zero, produzindo textura irregular que perturba o fluxo de ar e aumenta arrasto e peso.",
    "whenUsed": "When rime ice is encountered, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger rime icing, descend and maintain four thousand, say intensity.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, descending four thousand, moderate rime icing, will advise when clear.",
    "icaoQuestion": "You enter cloud at five thousand feet with a temperature of minus six Celsius and see opaque, rough ice forming on the windshield. What do you do and what do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would identify this as rime ice forming in freezing cloud. I would request an immediate altitude change to exit the icing layer and report the type and intensity to ATC. I would say I am experiencing moderate rime icing at five thousand, temperature minus six, and request descent or climb to warmer or clearer air. I would monitor power required and rotor performance while exiting, and I would divert if I cannot leave the icing conditions promptly. I would not continue in known icing in the H130.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Rime Ice — opaque, rough ice that forms when supercooled water droplets freeze on contact with the airframe, typically in stratiform cloud at temperatures well below freezing.\n\nRime ice is not a textbook curiosity. It changes rotor blade shape, adds weight, and can obscure antennas and the windshield. In Brazilian winter IFR — Curitiba, São Paulo plateau, Serra do Mar approaches — rime is the ice type crews most often report in layered cloud.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations, the aircraft is generally not certified for flight into known icing. Recognizing rime early, exiting the layer, and reporting clearly to ATC are Part 2 and Part 3 skills that protect performance and traffic awareness.\n\nUnderstanding how to describe rime ice in ICAO-standard English — intensity, altitude, and exit request — is essential for professional IFR communication.",
    "captainTeaching": "Rime ice looks harmless because it is white and rough — not glossy like clear ice. Do not trust appearance.\n\nRime changes the aerodynamic shape of blades and airfoils. Drag rises. Power required rises. In the H130, you feel it as more collective for the same airspeed and altitude.\n\nBrazilian winter IFR often puts you in stratiform layers over the plateau. That is classic rime territory: small droplets, cold air, long exposure if you stay in the layer.\n\nYour job is simple: recognize, exit, report.\n\nSay the type when you know it — rime — and the intensity. ATC turns that into a PIREP that protects the next crew.\n\nDo not negotiate with the layer. Climb, descend, or turn. If you cannot exit and performance is falling, declare the situation early. Ice does not wait for a perfect radio call.",
    "operationalContext": "You are IFR at six thousand feet toward Curitiba in layered stratus. Outside air temperature is minus eight Celsius. Opaque ice begins building on the windshield wiper and pitot mast — rough, white, granular.\n\nYou transmit:\n\nCuritiba Approach, ANAC123, moderate rime icing at six thousand, temperature minus eight, request descent to four thousand to exit icing.\n\nApproach: ANAC123, descend and maintain four thousand, report when clear of icing.\n\nYou leave six thousand. In warmer air below the layer, accretion stops. You report clear of icing and continue with caution.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, moderate rime icing at six thousand, request descent to four thousand.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would identify this as rime ice forming in freezing cloud. I would request an immediate altitude change to exit the icing layer and report the type and intensity to ATC. I would say I am experiencing moderate rime icing at five thousand, temperature minus six, and request descent or climb to warmer or clearer air. I would monitor power required and rotor performance while exiting, and I would divert if I cannot leave the icing conditions promptly. I would not continue in known icing in the H130.",
    "memoryTrick": "**RIME** — **R**ough opaque ice, **I**nstant freeze of small droplets, **M**ove out of the layer now, **E**xplain type and intensity to ATC.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When rime ice is encountered, the crew should:\n\nRime ice reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger rime icing, descend and maintain four thousand, say intensity.",
      "Center: ANAC123, previous aircraft reported moderate rime at five thousand.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, advise when clear of icing.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, say air temperature and icing type if able.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, diversion approved, say intentions."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, descending four thousand, moderate rime icing, will advise when clear.",
      "ANAC123, roger previous rime report at five thousand, monitoring.",
      "ANAC123, clear of icing at four thousand, temperature plus two.",
      "ANAC123, temperature minus eight, moderate rime ice, requesting descent.",
      "ANAC123, diverting to Congonhas due icing, request vectors."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Saying only \"ice\" without type or intensity.  \n  ✔ Report: moderate rime icing at five thousand, request descent.\n\n- ❌ Staying in the layer to \"see if it gets worse.\"  \n  ✔ Exit as soon as practicable; report and change altitude.\n\n- ❌ Mixing Portuguese weather slang on the frequency.  \n  ✔ Use ICAO English: rime icing, clear of icing, request diversion.\n\n- ❌ Forgetting to report when clear of icing.  \n  ✔ Advise ATC when accretion stops so the PIREP can be updated.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Moderate Rime Icing, Request Descent\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, MOD-er-it RYME ICE-ing, reh-KWEST deh-SENT\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Moderate → MOD-er-it (stress on first)\n- Rime → RYME (one syllable, long i)\n- Icing → ICE-ing (stress on first)\n- Descent → deh-SENT (stress on second)\n\nPractice:\n\nModerate rime icing... request descent to exit icing.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, moderate rime icing at six thousand, request descent to four thousand.",
