    "catalogId": "0367",
    "id": "0367",
    "displayTerm": "Structural Icing",
    "term": "structural icing",
    "slug": "structural-icing",
    "category": "Weather",
    "meaningEn": "Structural Icing is the accumulation of ice on the aircraft structure — including wings or rotor blades, fuselage, empennage, antennas, and probes — caused by flight in supercooled visible moisture, resulting in increased weight and drag, reduced lift, and possible degradation of control and systems performance.",
    "meaningPt": "Gelo estrutural / Structural Icing.\n\nAcúmulo de gelo na estrutura da aeronave — incluindo pás do rotor, fuselagem, estabilizadores, antenas e sondas — causado pelo voo em umidade visível super-resfriada, resultando em aumento de peso e arrasto, redução de sustentação e possível degradação de controle e desempenho de sistemas.",
    "whenUsed": "When structural icing is encountered or suspected, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger severe icing, descend immediately four thousand, priority approved.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, descending four thousand, severe structural icing, priority accepted.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Ice is forming on the airframe and you need increasing power to maintain altitude in cloud. How do you describe the situation and what do you request?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would treat this as structural icing affecting performance. I would request an immediate altitude change to exit icing and report severe or moderate structural icing with altitude and temperature if known. I would say I am unable to maintain altitude due to icing and request priority descent or diversion. I would monitor rotor performance and vibration, avoid remaining in the icing layer, and declare urgency if control or climb capability is threatened. In the H130 I would not continue into known icing.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Structural Icing — ice accretion on the airframe, rotor system, and external surfaces that changes aerodynamics, adds weight, and can critically degrade helicopter performance.\n\nStructural icing is a performance emergency in progress, not a weather footnote. Ice on main and tail rotor blades, fuselage, and antennas reduces lift, increases drag, and can lead to vibration, control issues, and inability to maintain altitude.\n\nFor H130 operations in Brazil — IFR over the Serra, winter arrivals into Curitiba and Porto Alegre, coastal cloud decks — structural icing demands immediate exit, clear ATC communication, and readiness to declare urgency if the aircraft cannot climb or maintain level flight.\n\nUnderstanding how to report structural icing and request priority handling in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Structural icing is where weather becomes aircraft performance.\n\nYou are not collecting ice for a report — you are losing the shape of the machine that keeps you flying.\n\nIn the H130, watch collective and power. If you need more and more collective to hold level flight in cloud near freezing, assume structural ice and leave the layer.\n\nBrazilian IFR winters give long stratiform exposures. That is how light icing becomes moderate, then severe, while crews hope it will stop.\n\nHope is not a procedure.\n\nExit first. Report with intensity. If you cannot hold altitude, say unable to maintain altitude and request priority. That language gets ATC moving.\n\nIf the situation is critical — vibration, rapid power loss, inability to climb — use urgency or distress phraseology. Structural icing kills options faster than most system failures.",
    "operationalContext": "You are IFR at eight thousand feet toward São Paulo. Ice is building on the windshield, skids, and visible blade roots. Collective is rising to hold altitude. Vibration is increasing.\n\nYou transmit:\n\nSão Paulo Approach, ANAC123, severe structural icing at eight thousand, unable to maintain altitude, request immediate descent and priority handling.\n\nApproach: ANAC123, descend and maintain four thousand, priority approved, say souls on board when able.\n\nYou descend. Ice stops accreting in warmer air. You report clear of icing and request vectors to the nearest suitable airport.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, severe structural icing at eight thousand, unable to maintain altitude, request immediate descent.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would treat this as structural icing affecting performance. I would request an immediate altitude change to exit icing and report severe or moderate structural icing with altitude and temperature if known. I would say I am unable to maintain altitude due to icing and request priority descent or diversion. I would monitor rotor performance and vibration, avoid remaining in the icing layer, and declare urgency if control or climb capability is threatened. In the H130 I would not continue into known icing.",
    "memoryTrick": "**ICE-OUT** — **I**dentify structural accretion, **C**ollective rising is your cue, **E**xit the layer now, **O**wn the radio call with intensity, **U**nable to maintain if altitude slips, **T**urn or divert if needed.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When structural icing is encountered or suspected, the crew should:\n\nStructural icing reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger severe icing, descend immediately four thousand, priority approved.",
      "Center: ANAC123, say icing intensity and souls on board.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, diversion approved, vectors to Congonhas, advise fuel remaining.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, previous aircraft reported severe structural icing at seven thousand.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, confirm able to maintain altitude."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, descending four thousand, severe structural icing, priority accepted.",
      "ANAC123, moderate structural icing, three souls, requesting descent.",
      "ANAC123, diverting Congonhas, vectors copied, fuel remaining one hour.",
      "ANAC123, roger severe icing PIREP at seven thousand, requesting lower.",
      "ANAC123, unable maintain eight thousand due icing, requesting immediate descent."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Softening the report: \"a little ice\" when performance is already degraded.  \n  ✔ Use intensity: moderate or severe structural icing, unable to maintain altitude.\n\n- ❌ Waiting for ATC to offer a level change.  \n  ✔ Request immediate descent or climb; state the operational need.\n\n- ❌ Continuing toward destination through the icing layer.  \n  ✔ Divert or reverse course if exit by altitude change is not available.\n\n- ❌ Omitting \"unable to maintain\" when altitude is slipping.  \n  ✔ That phrase triggers priority handling — use it when true.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Severe Structural Icing, Request Immediate Descent\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, seh-VEER STRUK-cher-ul ICE-ing, reh-KWEST ih-MEE-dee-it deh-SENT\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Severe → seh-VEER (stress on second)\n- Structural → STRUK-cher-ul (stress on first)\n- Icing → ICE-ing\n- Immediate → ih-MEE-dee-it (stress on second)\n\nPractice:\n\nSevere structural icing... request immediate descent.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, severe structural icing at eight thousand, unable to maintain altitude, request immediate descent.",
