    "catalogId": "0377",
    "id": "0377",
    "displayTerm": "METAR",
    "term": "metar",
    "slug": "metar",
    "category": "Weather",
    "meaningEn": "A METAR is a meteorological aerodrome report issued at fixed intervals (and as SPECI when conditions change significantly), providing current observed weather at an airport in a coded format that includes wind, visibility, runway visual range when applicable, present weather, cloud layers, temperature, dew point, and altimeter setting.",
    "meaningPt": "METAR / Informe Meteorológico de Aeródromo.\n\nInforme meteorológico de aeródromo emitido em intervalos fixos (e como SPECI quando as condições mudam significativamente), fornecendo o tempo observado atual em um aeroporto em formato codificado que inclui vento, visibilidade, alcance visual de pista quando aplicável, tempo presente, camadas de nuvens, temperatura, ponto de orvalho e ajuste do altímetro.",
    "whenUsed": "When using a METAR, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, Curitiba weather, wind calm, visibility two thousand meters, overcast four hundred, QNH one zero one five.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, weather copied, diverting Florianópolis due below minima.",
    "icaoQuestion": "What is a METAR and which elements do you check before an instrument approach?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "A METAR is the routine coded weather observation for an aerodrome. Before an instrument approach I check wind for runway selection, visibility and RVR if available against minima, present weather such as fog or thunderstorms, cloud layers for ceiling, temperature and dew point for fog or icing risk, and QNH for altitude reference. I also check the time of the report and any SPECI. If ceiling or visibility is below minima, I hold, delay, or divert rather than continue to a landing.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers METAR — the routine aviation weather report for an aerodrome, encoding wind, visibility, weather phenomena, clouds, temperature, dew point, and pressure in a standard international format.\n\nMETAR is the snapshot that drives go/no-go, approach selection, and ATC weather talk. For H130 operations in Brazil — Congonhas, Santos Dumont, Brasília, Manaus — reading METAR correctly is Part 4 literacy; using it to request the right approach or delay is Part 2 skill.\n\nUnderstanding how to decode and discuss METAR elements in ICAO English is essential for professional operations.",
    "captainTeaching": "METAR is the truth at a moment in time — coded so the world can read it the same way.\n\nLearn the groups cold: wind, visibility, weather, clouds, T/Td, QNH. Ceiling is the lowest broken or overcast layer that matters for minima.\n\nIn Brazil, mist and low overcast at Curitiba, fog at coastal fields, and CAVOK days that die in afternoon convection — all live in METAR and SPECI.\n\nPart 4: decode accurately. Part 2: when weather is below minima, say diverting due weather below minima. Do not invent a landing out of optimism.\n\nATIS is METAR's cousin on the frequency. Copy QNH. Compare with your briefed sheet. Fly the current number.",
    "operationalContext": "You are inbound to Curitiba. Latest METAR shows wind calm, visibility 2 000 meters in mist, overcast at 400 feet, temperature 8, dew point 8, QNH 1015. Your approach minima require higher ceiling.\n\nYou transmit:\n\nCuritiba Approach, ANAC123, request current weather Curitiba, destination below minima on last METAR, say intentions after weather.\n\nApproach issues the update. Ceiling remains 400. You divert.\n\nCuritiba Approach, ANAC123, diverting Florianópolis due weather below minima, request vectors.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, diverting due weather below minima, request vectors to alternate.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "A METAR is the routine coded weather observation for an aerodrome. Before an instrument approach I check wind for runway selection, visibility and RVR if available against minima, present weather such as fog or thunderstorms, cloud layers for ceiling, temperature and dew point for fog or icing risk, and QNH for altitude reference. I also check the time of the report and any SPECI. If ceiling or visibility is below minima, I hold, delay, or divert rather than continue to a landing.",
    "memoryTrick": "**METAR** — **M**easured now, **E**lements wind-vis-weather-cloud-T-QNH, **T**ime group matters, **A**pply to minima, **R**eroute if below.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When using a METAR, the crew should:\n\nMETAR operational use commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, Curitiba weather, wind calm, visibility two thousand meters, overcast four hundred, QNH one zero one five.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, say intentions, weather below landing minima.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, ATIS information Charlie current, advise received.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, SPECI issued, visibility now eight hundred meters in fog.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, diversion approved, advise alternate."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, weather copied, diverting Florianópolis due below minima.",
      "ANAC123, request current METAR / weather Congonhas.",
      "ANAC123, information Charlie received, QNH one zero one five.",
      "ANAC123, roger SPECI, visibility eight hundred, requesting hold.",
      "ANAC123, destination below minima, request vectors to alternate."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Reading temperature as ceiling or mixing SCT with ceiling.  \n  ✔ Ceiling = lowest BKN or OVC (or vertical visibility); SCT is not ceiling.\n\n- ❌ Using an old METAR when SPECI / ATIS has updated.  \n  ✔ Always use the latest observation before committing.\n\n- ❌ Saying \"bad weather\" instead of METAR elements.  \n  ✔ State visibility, ceiling, and below minima when relevant.\n\n- ❌ Ignoring dew point spread in Brazilian fog season.  \n  ✔ T/Td close together warns of fog — plan early.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Request Current Weather, Destination Below Minima\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, reh-KWEST KUR-ent WETH-er, des-ti-NAY-shun bih-LOH MIN-ih-muh\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- METAR → MEE-tar or MET-ar (common aviation: MAY-tar / MET-ar — use clear syllables)\n- Visibility → viz-ih-BIL-ih-tee\n- Ceiling → SEE-ling\n- Minima → MIN-ih-muh\n\nPractice:\n\nRequest current weather... visibility... ceiling... below minima.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, diverting due weather below minima, request vectors to alternate.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "TAF",
      "SPECI",
      "Ceiling Below Minimums",
      "Visibility Below Minimums",
      "ATIS",
      "Altimeter Setting"
    ],
