    "id": "0385",
    "displayTerm": "Weight and Balance",
    "term": "weight and balance",
    "slug": "weight-and-balance",
    "category": "Performance",
    "meaningEn": "Weight and Balance is the process of determining the aircraft's total weight and center of gravity location, ensuring both remain within the approved envelope for the intended flight phase.",
    "meaningPt": "Peso e balanceamento / Weight and Balance.\n\nProcesso de determinar o peso total da aeronave e a localização do centro de gravidade, garantindo que ambos permaneçam dentro do envelope aprovado para a fase de voo pretendida.",
    "whenUsed": "When managing weight and balance, the crew should:",
    "example": "Ground: ANAC123, advise ready to taxi.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, negative ready, request delay for weight and balance.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Ground asks if you are ready to taxi. Your weight and balance is not yet within limits after a last-minute load change. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would say: ANAC123, negative ready, request delay for weight and balance adjustment. I would advise when within limits and ready to taxi. I would not accept a taxi clearance while overweight or out of CG. Clear delay language keeps ATC informed and keeps the aircraft safe.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Weight and Balance — the calculation and control of aircraft total weight and the distribution of that weight so the center of gravity remains within approved limits for safe flight.\n\nWeight and Balance is not a ground formality. Incorrect loading changes performance, stability, and controllability — and may make takeoff or landing illegal and unsafe.\n\nFor H130 operations in Brazil — passenger shifts, cargo, fuel burn, and offshore loads — weight and balance must be verified before departure and respected when load changes. Discussing load-related delays or limitations with ATC requires clear ICAO English.\n\nThis lesson prepares you for Part 2, Part 3, and Part 4 communication.",
    "captainTeaching": "Weight and balance is the first performance calculation — before V-speeds, before takeoff charts, before \"ready.\"\n\nIf the load is wrong, nothing else matters. Offload. Redistribute. Delay. Then go.\n\nIn the H130, a few passengers or bags shifting aft can move CG quickly. Brief the load. Watch last-minute changes. Recalculate.\n\nWhen you need time on the ramp, tell ATC: request delay, weight and balance adjustment. Do not invent a radio problem to buy time. Honest operational language is respected.\n\nNever taxi while \"finishing the numbers.\" Either you are within limits or you are not ready.",
    "operationalContext": "At Congonhas, ground loads an extra passenger at the last minute. Your H130 takeoff weight would exceed the performance limit for the hot afternoon.\n\nYou call before taxi:\n\nSão Paulo Congonhas Ground, ANAC123, request delay, weight and balance adjustment, unable to depart at current load.\n\nGround: ANAC123, roger, hold position, advise when ready.\n\nAfter offloading baggage:\n\nANAC123, ready to taxi, weight and balance within limits.\n\nYou protected the flight with a clear delay request — not a rushed departure.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, negative ready, request delay for weight and balance adjustment.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would say: ANAC123, negative ready, request delay for weight and balance adjustment. I would advise when within limits and ready to taxi. I would not accept a taxi clearance while overweight or out of CG. Clear delay language keeps ATC informed and keeps the aircraft safe.",
    "memoryTrick": "**BALANCE** — **B**efore taxi, calculate, **A**rms and stations correct, **L**imits for weight and CG, **A**djust load if needed, **N**ever rush last-minute changes, **C**all ATC for delay clearly, **E**xecute departure only within envelope.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When managing weight and balance, the crew should:\n\nWeight and Balance control includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Ground: ANAC123, advise ready to taxi.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, roger delay for loading, hold position.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, say reason for delay.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, taxi when ready, no rush.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, unable departure due weight — confirm intentions."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, negative ready, request delay for weight and balance.",
      "ANAC123, holding position, adjusting load.",
      "ANAC123, delay for weight reduction, will advise ready.",
      "ANAC123, ready to taxi, weight and balance within limits.",
      "ANAC123, unable departure overweight, requesting offload time."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Departing after a last-minute passenger without recalculating.  \n  ✔ Recalculate weight and CG after every load change.\n\n- ❌ Saying \"not ready\" without a reason when delay is operational.  \n  ✔ State: delay for weight and balance / load adjustment.\n\n- ❌ Confusing maximum structural weight with performance-limited weight.  \n  ✔ Use the more restrictive limit for the conditions.\n\n- ❌ Ignoring CG when total weight is under maximum.  \n  ✔ Weight and CG are both required — either can stop the flight.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Request Delay for Weight and Balance Adjustment\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, reh-KWEST di-LAY for WAIT and BAL-ans uh-JUST-ment\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Delay → di-LAY\n- Weight → WAIT\n- Balance → BAL-ans\n- Adjustment → uh-JUST-ment (stress on second)\n\nPractice:\n\nRequest delay... weight and balance adjustment.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, negative ready, request delay for weight and balance adjustment.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "Center of Gravity Limits",
      "Maximum Takeoff Weight",
      "Maximum Landing Weight",
      "Takeoff Performance",
      "Density Altitude",
      "Load Manifest"
    ],
