    "catalogId": "0387",
    "id": "0387",
    "displayTerm": "Maximum Takeoff Weight",
    "term": "maximum takeoff weight",
    "slug": "maximum-takeoff-weight",
    "category": "Performance",
    "meaningEn": "Maximum Takeoff Weight is the maximum weight approved for takeoff, which may be the structural certified maximum or a lower weight limited by runway, climb, obstacle, or environmental performance for the specific departure.",
    "meaningPt": "Peso máximo de decolagem / Maximum Takeoff Weight (MTOW).\n\nPeso máximo aprovado para decolagem, que pode ser o máximo estrutural certificado ou um peso menor limitado por pista, subida, obstáculos ou condições ambientais para a partida específica.",
    "whenUsed": "When dealing with MTOW, the crew should:",
    "example": "Ground: ANAC123, advise ready to taxi.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, negative ready, above maximum takeoff weight for conditions.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Your aircraft is below structural MTOW but above the performance-limited takeoff weight for today's density altitude. Can you depart? What do you tell Ground?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I cannot depart. The applicable limit is the lower performance-limited weight. I would say: ANAC123, negative ready, above performance-limited takeoff weight, request delay for offload. After weight is within the performance limit, I would call ready. Structural MTOW alone is not sufficient authorization.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Maximum Takeoff Weight (MTOW) — the highest weight at which the aircraft is certified or performance-allowed to begin the takeoff, limited by structure, performance, or both.\n\nMTOW is a hard limit. Exceeding it is illegal and unsafe: climb gradients, reject margins, and structural loads are all based on approved weights.\n\nFor H130 Brazilian operations — hot days, high density altitude, and short pads — the performance-limited takeoff weight is often below structural MTOW. You must know the difference for Part 2 and Part 4 English and for ramp decisions with ATC.",
    "captainTeaching": "Maximum takeoff weight has two faces: structural and performance.\n\nStructural is the certified ceiling. Performance is what today's runway, temperature, and obstacles allow. You fly the lower number.\n\nIn Brazil's heat, the H130 often hits performance limits first. Do not argue with the chart because the placard MTOW is higher.\n\nIf you are heavy — offload. Tell ATC: delay for weight reduction, above takeoff weight for conditions. Clear and professional.\n\nNever \"burn down to weight\" by idling with a taxi clearance if you are still above limits — fix the load, then call ready.",
    "operationalContext": "Structural MTOW allows your planned H130 load. Afternoon temperature at Congonhas does not. Performance charts limit takeoff weight below your current ramp weight.\n\nYou call:\n\nSão Paulo Congonhas Ground, ANAC123, unable departure, above performance-limited takeoff weight, request delay for offload.\n\nGround: ANAC123, roger, hold position, advise ready.\n\nAfter offloading:\n\nANAC123, ready to taxi, takeoff weight within limits.\n\nYou respected the lower limit — the one that matters today.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, negative ready, above performance-limited takeoff weight, request delay for offload.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I cannot depart. The applicable limit is the lower performance-limited weight. I would say: ANAC123, negative ready, above performance-limited takeoff weight, request delay for offload. After weight is within the performance limit, I would call ready. Structural MTOW alone is not sufficient authorization.",
    "memoryTrick": "**MTOW** — **M**ore restrictive limit wins, **T**emperature and density cut weight, **O**ffload before ready, **W**arn ATC of delay clearly.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When dealing with MTOW, the crew should:\n\nMTOW decision-making includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Ground: ANAC123, advise ready to taxi.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, roger delay for weight reduction.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, say reason unable to depart.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, taxi when weight confirmed within limits.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, performance limited departure, full runway available."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, negative ready, above maximum takeoff weight for conditions.",
      "ANAC123, request delay for offload, weight reduction.",
      "ANAC123, unable departure overweight, holding position.",
      "ANAC123, ready to taxi, takeoff weight within limits.",
      "ANAC123, performance limited, request full runway available."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Using only structural MTOW and ignoring performance charts.  \n  ✔ Use the more restrictive weight for today's conditions.\n\n- ❌ Calling ready while still above the applicable takeoff weight.  \n  ✔ Offload first; then ready to taxi.\n\n- ❌ Not explaining the delay to ATC.  \n  ✔ State: delay for weight reduction / above takeoff weight for conditions.\n\n- ❌ Adding last-minute fuel without rechecking takeoff weight.  \n  ✔ Recalculate after any fuel or load change.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Above Maximum Takeoff Weight, Request Delay for Offload\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, uh-BUV MAK-si-mum TAKE-off WAIT, reh-KWEST di-LAY for OFF-lohd\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Maximum → MAK-si-mum\n- Takeoff → TAKE-off\n- Weight → WAIT\n- Offload → OFF-lohd\n\nPractice:\n\nAbove maximum takeoff weight... request delay for offload.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, negative ready, above performance-limited takeoff weight, request delay for offload.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "Takeoff Performance",
      "Weight and Balance",
      "Density Altitude",
      "Maximum Landing Weight",
      "Obstacle Clearance",
      "Runway Length Limitation"
    ],
