    "displayTerm": "Runway Length Limitation",
    "term": "runway length limitation",
    "slug": "runway-length-limitation",
    "category": "Performance",
    "meaningEn": "Runway Length Limitation means that the available takeoff or landing distance is less than the distance required by the aircraft performance calculation for the actual weight, wind, and surface conditions, making the operation unsafe or non-compliant unless the plan is changed.",
    "meaningPt": "Limitação por comprimento de pista / Runway Length Limitation.\n\nCondição em que a distância disponível para decolagem ou pouso é menor que a distância exigida pelo cálculo de desempenho da aeronave para o peso, vento e condições de superfície reais, tornando a operação insegura ou não conforme a menos que o plano seja alterado.",
    "whenUsed": "When runway length is limiting, the crew should:",
    "example": "Tower: ANAC123, intersection departure available, advise able.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, unable intersection, request full length.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Tower offers an intersection departure. Your takeoff requires full runway length. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would say: ANAC123, unable intersection departure, runway length limited, request full length. I would not accept a shorter takeoff run than calculated. If full length is not available, I would delay, reduce weight, or cancel. Clear limitation language helps ATC re-sequence without argument.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Runway Length Limitation — the operational condition in which available runway length is insufficient for the calculated takeoff or landing distance under current weight and environmental conditions.\n\nRunway Length Limitation is a hard stop on the plan. If the runway is too short for the numbers, you change weight, runway, or destination — you do not hope.\n\nFor H130 Brazilian operations — Santos Dumont, short municipal strips, and intersection departures — runway length often limits the mission. Communicating that limitation to ATC is essential Part 2 and Part 3 English.",
    "captainTeaching": "Runway length is a number match: required versus available.\n\nIf required is greater — stop the plan. Full length, other runway, less weight, or divert.\n\nIntersection departures steal length. If you are length-limited, say unable intersection every time. Habit saves you on the day you are tired.\n\nIn Brazil, Santos Dumont and short strips punish complacency. The H130 can use small areas — but wet surfaces, weight, and obstacles still demand real distance calculations.\n\nNOTAMs that shorten the runway are easy to miss. Read them. Recalculate. Speak up.",
    "operationalContext": "Santos Dumont. Your H130 landing calculation at current weight on a wet runway requires more distance than available with the reported tailwind.\n\nYou call:\n\nSantos Dumont Tower, ANAC123, runway length insufficient for current conditions, request opposite runway or diversion.\n\nTower: ANAC123, opposite runway available in five minutes, orbit east.\n\nYou respond:\n\nANAC123, orbiting east, expecting opposite runway.\n\nLength limitation stated — plan changed before short final.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, unable intersection, runway length limited, request full length.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would say: ANAC123, unable intersection departure, runway length limited, request full length. I would not accept a shorter takeoff run than calculated. If full length is not available, I would delay, reduce weight, or cancel. Clear limitation language helps ATC re-sequence without argument.",
    "memoryTrick": "**LENGTH** — **L**ook up available distance, **E**valuate required from charts, **N**ever take intersection if short, **G**et full length from ATC, **T**ransfer to other runway or divert, **H**eed NOTAMs that shorten the strip.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When runway length is limiting, the crew should:\n\nRunway Length Limitation planning includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Tower: ANAC123, intersection departure available, advise able.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, full length available, line up and wait.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, displaced threshold, available landing distance reduced.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, say runway requirement.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, runway works, length reduced, advise intentions."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, unable intersection, request full length.",
      "ANAC123, full length, lining up and waiting.",
      "ANAC123, displaced threshold copied, assessing landing distance.",
      "ANAC123, require full runway available, performance limited.",
      "ANAC123, runway length insufficient, requesting diversion."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Accepting intersection departure when full length is required.  \n  ✔ Unable intersection, request full length.\n\n- ❌ Ignoring displaced threshold reductions in available distance.  \n  ✔ Recalculate with the reduced LDA/TORA from ATIS or NOTAM.\n\n- ❌ Assuming helicopter operations never have runway length issues.  \n  ✔ Weight, wet surface, and pad size still limit the H130.\n\n- ❌ Waiting until lined up to reject a short runway plan.  \n  ✔ State the limitation before accepting the clearance.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Unable Intersection, Request Full Length Runway\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, un-AY-bul in-ter-SEK-shun, reh-KWEST FULL length RUN-way\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Unable → un-AY-bul\n- Intersection → in-ter-SEK-shun\n- Full → FULL\n- Length → LENGTH\n\nPractice:\n\nUnable intersection... request full length runway.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, unable intersection, runway length limited, request full length.",
