    "catalogId": "0390",
    "id": "0390",
    "displayTerm": "Obstacle Clearance",
    "term": "obstacle clearance",
    "slug": "obstacle-clearance",
    "category": "Performance",
    "meaningEn": "Obstacle Clearance is the maintenance of required minimum distances from terrain and obstacles, achieved through published procedures, climb performance, and crew adherence to altitude and tracking constraints.",
    "meaningPt": "Afastamento de obstáculos / Obstacle Clearance.\n\nManutenção das distâncias mínimas exigidas em relação ao terreno e aos obstáculos, obtida por procedimentos publicados, desempenho de subida e cumprimento pela tripulação das restrições de altitude e de trajetória.",
    "whenUsed": "When ensuring obstacle clearance, the crew should:",
    "example": "Clearance: ANAC123, cleared via SID, climb gradient required.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, unable SID climb gradient, request alternate departure.",
    "icaoQuestion": "The SID requires a climb gradient your aircraft cannot meet at current weight. ATC has already issued the SID clearance. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would not accept the SID as usable: ANAC123, unable SID climb gradient at current weight, request alternate departure or delay for weight reduction. A clearance does not create performance. I would remain on the ground until an obstacle-safe plan exists. Clear inability language allows ATC to issue a radar departure or different SID.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Obstacle Clearance — the requirement to maintain a safe vertical and lateral margin from terrain and obstacles during takeoff, climb, approach, and missed approach.\n\nObstacle Clearance is why departure procedures, climb gradients, and approach minima exist. It is performance and procedure together.\n\nFor H130 Brazilian operations — city helipads, Congonhas rising terrain, coastal cliffs, and offshore platforms — obstacles define where you can go and how you must climb. Discussing inability to meet a climb gradient or requesting an alternate departure in ICAO English is Part 2, Part 3, and Part 4 material.",
    "captainTeaching": "Obstacle clearance is non-negotiable.\n\nProcedures assume you can climb and track as published. If performance says you cannot — change weight or change procedure before you take off.\n\nIn Brazilian terrain — Serra do Mar, coastal hills, city towers — the H130's flexibility in visual conditions does not cancel IFR gradient requirements. Visual terrain clearance when approved is a specific clearance, not a casual substitute.\n\nOn approach, minima and missed approach climbs exist for obstacles. Do not dive below minima hoping to \"see and avoid\" in IMC.\n\nBrief obstacles. Meet the gradient. Or say unable.",
    "operationalContext": "Departure from a mountain-adjacent field in southern Brazil. The SID requires a steep climb gradient. Your H130 at current weight and density altitude cannot meet it.\n\nYou call before taxi:\n\nANAC123, unable SID climb gradient at current weight, request alternate departure or delay for weight reduction.\n\nClearance Delivery: ANAC123, roger, expect radar departure, maintain visual with terrain, climb as soon as practicable to five thousand.\n\nYou respond:\n\nANAC123, radar departure, climb five thousand, wilco.\n\nObstacle clearance protected by an honest performance call.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, unable SID climb gradient at current weight, request alternate departure.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would not accept the SID as usable: ANAC123, unable SID climb gradient at current weight, request alternate departure or delay for weight reduction. A clearance does not create performance. I would remain on the ground until an obstacle-safe plan exists. Clear inability language allows ATC to issue a radar departure or different SID.",
    "memoryTrick": "**OBSTACLE** — **O**bey published gradients, **B**rief terrain before departure, **S**ay unable if performance fails, **T**rack the SID precisely, **A**lternate departure when needed, **C**limb to safe altitude, **L**eave minima alone in IMC, **E**xecute missed approach as published.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When ensuring obstacle clearance, the crew should:\n\nObstacle Clearance planning includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Clearance: ANAC123, cleared via SID, climb gradient required.",
      "Departure: ANAC123, climb via SID, comply with restrictions.",
      "Radar: ANAC123, radar departure approved, maintain terrain clearance visually.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, missed approach as published, climb to four thousand.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, advise able to meet climb gradient."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, unable SID climb gradient, request alternate departure.",
      "ANAC123, climb via SID, wilco.",
      "ANAC123, radar departure, maintaining terrain clearance.",
      "ANAC123, missed approach as published, climbing four thousand.",
      "ANAC123, unable climb gradient at current weight, request delay."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Accepting a SID without checking climb gradient capability.  \n  ✔ Verify gradient vs performance before accepting the clearance.\n\n- ❌ Relying on visual see-and-avoid in IMC for obstacles.  \n  ✔ Fly published altitudes and procedures for obstacle clearance.\n\n- ❌ Not advising ATC when unable to meet a restriction.  \n  ✔ State unable climb gradient / unable altitude restriction early.\n\n- ❌ Reducing margin on missed approach to \"make the field.\"  \n  ✔ Execute the published missed approach for obstacle protection.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Unable Climb Gradient, Request Alternate Departure\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, un-AY-bul KLYME GRAY-dee-unt, reh-KWEST AWL-ter-nit di-PAR-cher\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Unable → un-AY-bul\n- Climb → KLYME\n- Gradient → GRAY-dee-unt\n- Alternate → AWL-ter-nit\n- Departure → di-PAR-cher\n\nPractice:\n\nUnable climb gradient... request alternate departure.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, unable SID climb gradient at current weight, request alternate departure.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "Takeoff Performance",
      "SID Clearance",
      "Climb Gradient",
      "Minimum Safe Altitude",
      "Missed Approach",
      "Density Altitude"
    ],
