    "meaningEn": "Stick Shaker is a stall warning device that vibrates the control column when the aircraft approaches a critical angle of attack, providing a tactile cue that aerodynamic stall is imminent and immediate recovery is required.",
    "meaningPt": "Stick shaker / agitador do manche.\n\nDispositivo de aviso de estol que vibra a coluna de comando quando a aeronave se aproxima de um ângulo de ataque crítico, fornecendo um alerta tátil de que o estol aerodinâmico é iminente e a recuperação imediata é necessária.",
    "whenUsed": "When the Stick Shaker activates, the crew should:",
    "example": "Tower: ANAC123, roger stick shaker, cleared go-around, climb and maintain two thousand.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, going around, stick shaker, climbing two thousand.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Explain stick shaker and what you would say to ATC if it activates on approach.?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Stick shaker is a tactile stall warning that vibrates the control column near critical angle of attack. I would reduce angle of attack, add power, and go around. Then I would say: ANAC123, going around, stick shaker, recovering, request climb two thousand. On the H130 there is no stick shaker, but I would use the same urgency and clear English for any critical low-energy recovery.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Stick Shaker — the tactile stall warning that vibrates the control column when the aircraft approaches a critical angle of attack.\n\nStick Shaker language appears frequently in ICAO English exams and airline phraseology, even for helicopter pilots who must demonstrate fixed-wing system vocabulary.\n\nThe H130 does not use a stick shaker. Captain Delta still requires you to speak this concept fluently for Part 2 and Part 3 exams, and to map the same urgency onto helicopter low-energy and low-rotor-RPM emergencies in Brazilian operations.\n\nUnderstanding how to report stick shaker activation, recovery, and intentions is essential professional English.",
    "captainTeaching": "Stick shaker is exam English you must own — even in a helicopter.\n\nICAO raters expect the vocabulary: stick shaker, stall warning, recovering, going around. If you freeze on the term because \"we fly H130,\" you lose points and, worse, you lose a communication tool.\n\nMap it: stick shaker equals critical angle of attack or critical energy state. In the H130, low rotor RPM or settling with power demands the same sequence — fly, recover, then call.\n\nDo not invent long stories on frequency. Three elements: what happened, what you are doing, what you need. Stick shaker. Recovering. Request climb.\n\nBrazilian ops around Congonhas and Santos Dumont leave little margin on short final. If energy collapses, go around and say why.",
    "operationalContext": "You are briefing a Part 2 oral scenario at Congonhas while operating H130 IFR training flights in the São Paulo terminal area.\n\nThe examiner asks you to demonstrate stick shaker phraseology as if on a jet approach.\n\nYou transmit the standard call:\n\nCongonhas Tower, ANAC123, going around, stick shaker, recovering, request climb two thousand.\n\nTower acknowledges and clears the missed approach. You explain to the examiner that the H130 has no stick shaker, but the communication standard is identical for any critical low-energy recovery.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, going around, stick shaker, recovering, request climb two thousand.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Stick shaker is a tactile stall warning that vibrates the control column near critical angle of attack. I would reduce angle of attack, add power, and go around. Then I would say: ANAC123, going around, stick shaker, recovering, request climb two thousand. On the H130 there is no stick shaker, but I would use the same urgency and clear English for any critical low-energy recovery.",
    "memoryTrick": "**SHAKE** — **S**top pulling, **H**ead nose down, **A**dd power, **K**eep wings level, **E**xplain to ATC: stick shaker.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When the Stick Shaker activates, the crew should:\n\nStick Shaker reporting commonly includes:",
