    "catalogId": "0398",
    "id": "0398",
    "displayTerm": "Stick Pusher",
    "term": "stick pusher",
    "slug": "stick-pusher",
    "category": "Aircraft Systems",
    "meaningEn": "Stick Pusher is an automatic stall-protection system that applies a forward force on the control column when a critical angle of attack is reached, reducing pitch attitude to prevent aerodynamic stall or to assist recovery.",
    "meaningPt": "Stick pusher / empurrador do manche.\n\nSistema automático de proteção contra estol que aplica força à frente na coluna de comando quando um ângulo de ataque crítico é atingido, reduzindo a atitude de arfagem para prevenir o estol aerodinâmico ou auxiliar a recuperação.",
    "whenUsed": "When the Stick Pusher activates, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger stick pusher, climb and maintain three thousand, turn left heading two seven zero.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, climbing three thousand, left heading two seven zero, stick pusher recovering.",
    "icaoQuestion": "What is a stick pusher, and what would you report to ATC if it activates?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "A stick pusher automatically pushes the control column forward at critical angle of attack to prevent or recover from stall. I would allow the recovery, add power, and go around. I would report: ANAC123, going around, stick pusher, recovering, request climb three thousand. The H130 has no stick pusher, but I would use the same clear structure for any critical stall-protection or low-energy recovery.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Stick Pusher — the automatic system that pushes the control column forward when the aircraft reaches a critical angle of attack, forcing a reduction in pitch to prevent or recover from stall.\n\nStick Pusher is advanced stall-protection vocabulary in ICAO English exams and transport-category operations.\n\nThe H130 does not have a stick pusher. Captain Delta still requires fluent exam English for this system, plus the operational discipline to accept automatic or procedural nose-down recovery cues and to communicate clearly during Brazilian IFR recoveries.",
    "captainTeaching": "Stick pusher is the airplane taking the nose away from you to save the wing.\n\nExam English demands the exact term. \"The stick pushed alone\" is not enough. Say stick pusher.\n\nDo not narrate a fight with the system on frequency. Say: stick pusher, recovering, request climb. If you must declare: mayday, stall recovery.\n\nFor H130 pilots, the lesson is acceptance of recovery geometry. When the aircraft — or the procedure — demands nose down and energy restoration, comply first. Ego kills more approaches than stick pushers do.\n\nAround Brazilian high-density airports, a stick-pusher-style recovery means an immediate missed approach and a clean call so Tower can move traffic.",
    "operationalContext": "During an ICAO English check in São Paulo, you are asked to describe stick pusher activation on a jet approach into Guarulhos, then relate it to H130 recovery priorities.\n\nYou demonstrate the radio call:\n\nGuarulhos Approach, ANAC123, going around, stick pusher, recovering, request climb three thousand, vectors.\n\nApproach clears you and asks if you declare an emergency. You reply with status and intentions, then brief that the H130 has no pusher but the communication pattern — system name, action, request — remains the standard.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, going around, stick pusher, recovering, request climb three thousand.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "A stick pusher automatically pushes the control column forward at critical angle of attack to prevent or recover from stall. I would allow the recovery, add power, and go around. I would report: ANAC123, going around, stick pusher, recovering, request climb three thousand. The H130 has no stick pusher, but I would use the same clear structure for any critical stall-protection or low-energy recovery.",
    "memoryTrick": "**PUSH** — **P**ermit the nose down, **U**nload the wing, **S**tate stick pusher to ATC, **H**ead for a safe climb.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When the Stick Pusher activates, the crew should:\n\nStick Pusher reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger stick pusher, climb and maintain three thousand, turn left heading two seven zero.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, roger going around, wind calm, report when recovered.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, say if you declare emergency, radar vectors available.",
      "Control: ANAC123, priority handling approved, advise souls on board and fuel remaining when able.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, when ready, expect ILS runway two seven right."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, climbing three thousand, left heading two seven zero, stick pusher recovering.",
      "ANAC123, going around, will report when recovered.",
      "ANAC123, pan-pan, stick pusher on approach, recovering, request vectors.",
      "ANAC123, souls four, fuel one hour three zero, request return.",
      "ANAC123, ready for ILS runway two seven right."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Overriding the pusher to hold the glidepath.  \n  ✔ Respect the pusher. Recover first, then re-brief the approach.\n\n- ❌ Using vague language: \"controls moved by themselves.\"  \n  ✔ Say stick pusher — the standard ICAO exam term.\n\n- ❌ Declaring nothing because the recovery was quick.  \n  ✔ Still report the event so ATC can protect traffic.\n\n- ❌ Ignoring the topic as \"jet only.\"  \n  ✔ Master the English; apply the recovery discipline to the H130.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Stick Pusher, Recovering, Request Climb\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, STIK PUSH-er, ree-KUH-vuh-ring, reh-KWEST KLIME\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Stick → STIK\n- Pusher → PUSH-er (stress on first)\n- Climb → KLIME\n\nPractice:\n\nStick pusher... recovering... request climb.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, going around, stick pusher, recovering, request climb three thousand.",
