    "catalogId": "0403",
    "id": "0403",
    "displayTerm": "Minimum Safe Altitude",
    "term": "minimum safe altitude",
    "slug": "minimum-safe-altitude",
    "category": "Navigation",
    "meaningEn": "Minimum Safe Altitude is the lowest altitude that provides a specified clearance above the highest terrain or obstacle within a defined sector or radius around a navigation facility or aerodrome, used for emergency and situational reference during instrument flight.",
    "meaningPt": "Altitude mínima de segurança (MSA).\n\nMenor altitude que proporciona uma margem especificada acima do terreno ou obstáculo mais elevado dentro de um setor ou raio definido em torno de um auxílio à navegação ou aeródromo, usada como referência de emergência e consciência situacional em voo por instrumentos.",
    "whenUsed": "When using Minimum Safe Altitude, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, descend and maintain three thousand, minimum vectoring altitude.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, unable two thousand five hundred, below MSA, maintaining three thousand five hundred.",
    "icaoQuestion": "ATC clears you below the charted MSA while you are on random vectors. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would refuse the clearance if it does not provide terrain clearance for my position. I would say: ANAC123, unable two thousand five hundred, below MSA, request three thousand five hundred. I would maintain a safe altitude and accept a revised clearance that respects terrain until established on a published procedure allowing lower.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Minimum Safe Altitude — the published or calculated altitude that provides terrain and obstacle clearance within a defined area, used for emergency drift-down, lost procedures, and situational awareness.\n\nMSA is not optional knowledge. It is the floor beneath your IFR plan.\n\nIn the H130, MSA awareness is critical on Brazilian IFR routes across the Serra do Mar, Minas Gerais highlands, and coastal transitions where a descent below MSA without reference can be fatal. Part 2 and Part 4 require you to discuss and request altitudes with reference to MSA when needed.",
    "captainTeaching": "MSA is the altitude that keeps rock out of the windshield when the plan falls apart.\n\nBrief it before top of descent. Know the highest sector on your arrival. In the H130, you can descend steeply — that capability is not permission to bust MSA.\n\n\"Unable\" is professional English, not conflict. ANAC123, unable, below MSA, request higher. Controllers in Brazil understand terrain. They need you to say it.\n\nPart 4 discussion often asks when you climb to MSA: navigation failure, position uncertain, or clearance conflict with terrain. Answer with the altitude and the reason.\n\nNever let politeness put you below a safe altitude.",
    "operationalContext": "You are IFR in your H130 toward Confins. Approach issues descend and maintain two thousand five hundred on a vector.\n\nYour charted MSA for the sector is three thousand five hundred. You are not yet established on a published segment that allows lower.\n\nYou transmit:\n\nConfins Approach, ANAC123, unable two thousand five hundred, below MSA, request three thousand five hundred.\n\nApproach climbs you and issues a revised vector for the approach from a safe altitude.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, unable two thousand five hundred, below MSA, request three thousand five hundred.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would refuse the clearance if it does not provide terrain clearance for my position. I would say: ANAC123, unable two thousand five hundred, below MSA, request three thousand five hundred. I would maintain a safe altitude and accept a revised clearance that respects terrain until established on a published procedure allowing lower.",
    "memoryTrick": "**MSA** — **M**aintain until published segment, **S**ay unable if clearance is lower, **A**scend when position is uncertain.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When using Minimum Safe Altitude, the crew should:\n\nMSA-related reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, descend and maintain three thousand, minimum vectoring altitude.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger unable, maintain three thousand five hundred, turn left heading zero one zero.",
      "Control: ANAC123, say altitude, confirm at or above MSA.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, when established on the localizer, cleared to descend with the procedure.",
      "Control: ANAC123, if lost communications, maintain last assigned or MSA, whichever higher, per procedure."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, unable two thousand five hundred, below MSA, maintaining three thousand five hundred.",
      "ANAC123, descending three thousand, minimum vectoring altitude.",
      "ANAC123, left heading zero one zero, maintaining three thousand five hundred.",
      "ANAC123, established localizer, descending with the procedure.",
      "ANAC123, request climb to MSA, position uncertain."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Accepting any descent clearance without checking MSA.  \n  ✔ Cross-check sector MSA before leaving a safe altitude.\n\n- ❌ Saying \"I think it's low\" without the word MSA.  \n  ✔ Use: unable, below MSA, request higher.\n\n- ❌ Descending below MSA because \"we are visual with some lights.\"  \n  ✔ Lights are not terrain clearance. Stay at MSA until the procedure allows lower.\n\n- ❌ Confusing MSA with airport elevation.  \n  ✔ MSA protects a sector — know which sector you are in.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Unable, Below MSA, Request Higher\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, un-AY-bul, bih-LOH EM-ESS-AY, reh-KWEST HY-er\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Unable → un-AY-bul\n- Below → bih-LOH\n- MSA → EM-ESS-AY (spell clearly)\n\nPractice:\n\nUnable... below MSA... request higher.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, unable two thousand five hundred, below MSA, request three thousand five hundred.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "Terrain Awareness Warning",
      "GPWS Warning",
      "Minimum Vectoring Altitude",
      "Lost Communications",
      "Crossing Restriction",
      "IFR Descent"
    ],
