    "id": "0406",
    "displayTerm": "Sling Load Operations",
    "term": "sling load operations",
    "slug": "sling-load-operations",
    "category": "Helicopter Operations",
    "meaningEn": "Sling Load Operations are helicopter flights in which external cargo is carried on a sling and cargo hook beneath the aircraft, requiring specialized hover techniques, load monitoring, and communication of load status and routing to ATC and ground crews.",
    "meaningPt": "Operações com carga externa / sling load.\n\nVoos de helicóptero em que a carga externa é transportada em linga e gancho de carga sob a aeronave, exigindo técnicas especializadas de pairado, monitoramento da carga e comunicação do status e da rota ao ATC e às equipes de solo.",
    "whenUsed": "When conducting Sling Load Operations, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Tower: ANAC123, roger sling load, cleared hover departure, remain clear of runway two five final.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, sling load, hover departure, remaining clear of final.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Describe what you report to ATC during a sling load flight from lift to release.?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would identify the flight as sling load, report load on and departure route, report on station for placement, then report load released and climb-out intentions. Example: ANAC123, sling load, load on, request hover departure not above five hundred; later ANAC123, load released, request climb one thousand five hundred. Clear status calls keep ATC and traffic safe.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Sling Load Operations — external load flights in which cargo is carried beneath the helicopter on a cargo hook and sling, requiring precise hover work, clear crew coordination, and specific ATC phraseology.\n\nSling load is highly relevant H130 work in Brazil: construction lifts, power-line support, remote resupply in the Amazon and highlands, and industrial sites near controlled airspace.\n\nYou must communicate load status, hover intentions, route constraints, and emergencies — including the possibility of jettison — in ICAO Part 2 and Part 3 English.",
    "captainTeaching": "Sling load English is status English: load on, on station, load released.\n\nATC cannot see the bag under your belly. They only know what you say.\n\nIn the H130, vertical reference and power margin define the lift. If the load starts to dance, fix it or put it down. Do not drag a runaway sling through a city frequency without a call.\n\nNear Brazilian controlled airports, stay predictable. Announce altitude caps. Report release before you climb through the circuit.\n\nIf the load threatens the aircraft, the next lesson — jettison — becomes this lesson's emergency exit. Brief it before the hook closes.",
    "operationalContext": "You are lifting a construction load in your H130 near Campinas, inside a control zone.\n\nYou transmit:\n\nCampinas Tower, ANAC123, sling load, load on, request hover departure to construction site north, not above five hundred feet.\n\nTower clears you and advises light aircraft in the circuit. On site:\n\nANAC123, on station, placing load, will report load released.\n\nAfter release:\n\nANAC123, load released, request climb one thousand five hundred, returning base.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, sling load, load on, request hover departure, not above five hundred.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would identify the flight as sling load, report load on and departure route, report on station for placement, then report load released and climb-out intentions. Example: ANAC123, sling load, load on, request hover departure not above five hundred; later ANAC123, load released, request climb one thousand five hundred. Clear status calls keep ATC and traffic safe.",
    "memoryTrick": "**SLING** — **S**ay sling load, **L**ift with load-on call, **I**nform on station, **N**otify load released, **G**o climb only after the call.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When conducting Sling Load Operations, the pilot should:\n\nSling Load reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Tower: ANAC123, roger sling load, cleared hover departure, remain clear of runway two five final.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, report load on and airborne.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, sling load approved not above five hundred, report on station.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, advise when load released, traffic inbound.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, roger load released, cleared climb one thousand five hundred."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, sling load, hover departure, remaining clear of final.",
      "ANAC123, load on, airborne, proceeding construction site.",
      "ANAC123, not above five hundred, will report on station.",
      "ANAC123, load released, requesting climb one thousand five hundred.",
      "ANAC123, returning base, load complete."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Departing with a load without telling ATC it is sling load.  \n  ✔ State sling load on first contact.\n\n- ❌ Climbing through the circuit immediately after release without a call.  \n  ✔ Report load released, then request climb.\n\n- ❌ Saying nothing while hovering for long periods in controlled airspace.  \n  ✔ Report on station and expected delay if placement takes time.\n\n- ❌ Using only Portuguese with the ground crew on the ATC frequency.  \n  ✔ Keep ATC frequency in ICAO English; use intercom/company for hook talk.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Sling Load, Load On, Request Departure\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, SLING LOHD, LOHD ON, reh-KWEST dih-PAR-cher\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Sling → SLING\n- Load → LOHD\n- Departure → dih-PAR-cher\n\nPractice:\n\nSling load... load on... load released.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, sling load, load on, request hover departure, not above five hundred.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "External Load Jettison",
      "Hover Taxi",
      "Helideck Operations",
      "Low-Level Operations",
      "Pan-Pan",
      "Construction Site Landing"
    ],
