    "id": "0414",
    "displayTerm": "Rotor Brake Failure",
    "term": "rotor brake failure",
    "slug": "rotor-brake-failure",
    "category": "Helicopter Operations",
    "meaningEn": "Rotor Brake Failure is a malfunction in which the rotor brake does not decelerate or hold the main rotor as designed after landing or shutdown, leaving the rotor turning longer than expected and requiring procedures to keep the area clear until the rotor can be stopped safely.",
    "meaningPt": "Falha do freio de rotor.\n\nMalfuncionamento em que o freio de rotor não desacelera ou retém o rotor principal conforme projetado após o pouso ou o desligamento, deixando o rotor girando por mais tempo que o esperado e exigindo procedimentos para manter a área livre até que o rotor possa ser parado com segurança.",
    "whenUsed": "When rotor brake failure occurs, the crew should:",
    "example": "Tower: ANAC123, roger rotor brake failure, keep personnel clear, assistance coordinated.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, rotor brake failure, personnel remaining clear, stand by.",
    "icaoQuestion": "After shutdown the rotor brake fails and blades keep turning. What do you tell Tower?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would report the failure and the hazard clearly: rotor brake failure, rotors still turning, keep all personnel clear, pad not available, requesting ground assistance. I would not allow passenger egress toward the disc. When the rotor is secured I would update: rotors stopped, pad clearing.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Rotor Brake Failure — inability of the rotor brake to stop or hold the main rotor after landing or shutdown, creating a prolonged turning-rotor hazard for passengers and ground crew.\n\nRotor brake failure is a ground emergency with airside consequences: the pad stays hot, people cannot approach, and the next aircraft cannot use the site until the rotor is secured by other means.\n\nFor H130 operations in Brazil — hospital pads, Congonhas stands, and offshore decks — you must report the failure, keep personnel clear, and request assistance without understating the hazard.\n\nUnderstanding how to communicate rotor brake failure in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Rotor brake failure English is perimeter English.\n\nYour first product on frequency is a clear keep-clear message. Your second is an honest pad-not-available.\n\nIn the H130, follow the AFM alternate procedure. Do not invent a \"quick stop\" that damages the transmission or throws a blade hazard at the crowd.\n\nBrazilian hospital and city pads are crowded. People will walk in if you sound uncertain. Sound certain: rotor brake failure, rotors still turning, keep clear.\n\nWhen the rotor finally stops, close the loop with ATC so the next flight can move. Silence after the emergency call creates a second problem — a stuck pad with no status.",
    "operationalContext": "You land your H130 at Santos Dumont helipad after a charter. You shut down and apply the rotor brake. The rotor does not decelerate normally.\n\nYou hold the cabin: nobody exits toward the blades. You call:\n\nTower, rotor brake failure, rotors still turning, keep all personnel clear of the aircraft, requesting ground assistance, pad not available.\n\nTower holds the next helicopter and sends ground crew with the approved securing procedure. Only after the rotor stops do you allow egress.",
    "sayItCoach": "rotor brake failure, rotors still turning, keep all personnel clear, pad not available.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would report the failure and the hazard clearly: rotor brake failure, rotors still turning, keep all personnel clear, pad not available, requesting ground assistance. I would not allow passenger egress toward the disc. When the rotor is secured I would update: rotors stopped, pad clearing.",
    "memoryTrick": "**STOP** — **S**ecure cabin (no egress), **T**ell ATC brake failed, **O**btain assistance, **P**ad unavailable until rotor stopped.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When rotor brake failure occurs, the crew should:\n\nRotor brake failure reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Tower: ANAC123, roger rotor brake failure, keep personnel clear, assistance coordinated.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, say if you require fire services.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, next helicopter holding, advise when rotor secured.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, confirm safe distance for approach to assist.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, roger rotors now stopped, report when pad clear."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, rotor brake failure, personnel remaining clear, stand by.",
      "ANAC123, negative fire services at this time, request maintenance assistance.",
      "ANAC123, wilco, will advise when rotor secured.",
      "ANAC123, remain clear until signaled, rotor still turning.",
      "ANAC123, rotors stopped, passengers disembarking, pad clear shortly."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Allowing passengers to exit \"pelo lado de trás\" while blades turn.  \n  ✔ Nobody approaches a turning rotor — report keep clear until stopped.\n\n- ❌ Saying only \"freio com problema\" without pad status.  \n  ✔ State rotor brake failure, rotors still turning, pad not available.\n\n- ❌ Forgetting to update when the rotor is finally secured.  \n  ✔ Close the loop so ATC can release the next arrival.\n\n- ❌ Requesting ambulance approach for patient transfer too early.  \n  ✔ Secure the rotor first; then clear medical approach.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** Rotor Brake Failure, Keep Personnel Clear\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, ROH-ter BRAYK FAYL-yer, keep per-suh-NEL KLEER\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Rotor → ROH-ter\n- Brake → BRAYK\n- Failure → FAYL-yer\n- Personnel → per-suh-NEL (stress on last)\n\nPractice:\n\nRotor brake failure... keep personnel clear.\n\nTogether:\n\nrotor brake failure, rotors still turning, keep all personnel clear, pad not available.",
