    "catalogId": "0417",
    "id": "0417",
    "displayTerm": "Pedal Failure",
    "term": "pedal failure",
    "slug": "pedal-failure",
    "category": "Helicopter Operations",
    "meaningEn": "Pedal Failure is a malfunction of the anti-torque pedal system that prevents normal yaw control through the tail rotor or equivalent anti-torque system, requiring immediate emergency procedures and an expedited landing, preferably with forward speed rather than a prolonged hover.",
    "meaningPt": "Falha dos pedais (antitorque).\n\nMalfuncionamento do sistema de pedais antitorque que impede o controle normal de guinada pelo rotor de cauda ou sistema antitorque equivalente, exigindo procedimentos de emergência imediatos e pouso expedito, de preferência com velocidade à frente em vez de pairado prolongado.",
    "whenUsed": "When pedal failure occurs, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, mayday acknowledged, cleared to Congonhas, expect runway one seven left, wind one eight zero at one two.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, mayday, pedal failure, unable hover, requesting Congonhas run-on.",
    "icaoQuestion": "You lose pedal control on approach to a confined helipad. What do you tell ATC?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would declare: Mayday mayday mayday, pedal failure, loss of yaw control, unable hover, requesting run-on landing at the nearest suitable runway, with position. I would discontinue the confined pad approach and give souls and fuel when able.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Pedal Failure — loss of normal anti-torque pedal control, compromising yaw control and requiring emergency procedures, careful airspeed management, and clear distress communication with ATC.\n\nPedal failure threatens heading control, especially in the hover and at low speed. The emergency is obvious in the cockpit; it must be equally clear on frequency.\n\nFor H130 operations in Brazil — confined pads, rooftop helipads, and low-speed city approaches — you must declare the failure, avoid unnecessary hover, and state landing intentions in ICAO English.\n\nUnderstanding how to report pedal failure in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Pedal failure English must include the operational limitation: unable hover.\n\nIf you only say \"pedal problem,\" ATC may still offer a rooftop. Say what you need: run-on landing, large area, wind preferred.\n\nIn the H130, yaw margin shrinks in the hover and in crosswinds. Brazilian hospital pads are often confined — reject them when anti-torque is gone.\n\nWind is not small talk in this emergency. Ask for it. Use it. Tell Tower you need a run-on if that is the plan.\n\nKeep the mayday clean: failure, limitation, destination. Then fly the approach you can still control.",
    "operationalContext": "On approach to a São Paulo hospital pad in your H130, left pedal authority is lost. You discontinue the pad approach and transmit:\n\nMayday mayday mayday, São Paulo Approach, pedal failure, loss of yaw control, unable hover, requesting run-on landing Congonhas, souls four, fuel one hour.\n\nApproach coordinates a runway arrival with wind and emergency services. You fly a running landing and report on ground.",
    "sayItCoach": "Mayday, pedal failure, unable hover, requesting run-on landing Congonhas.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would declare: Mayday mayday mayday, pedal failure, loss of yaw control, unable hover, requesting run-on landing at the nearest suitable runway, with position. I would discontinue the confined pad approach and give souls and fuel when able.",
    "memoryTrick": "**YAW** — **Y**ell mayday with pedal failure, **A**void hover, **W**ant run-on / wind / wide area.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When pedal failure occurs, the crew should:\n\nPedal failure reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, mayday acknowledged, cleared to Congonhas, expect runway one seven left, wind one eight zero at one two.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, unable hospital pad approved, proceed Congonhas for run-on.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, cleared to land runway one seven left, emergency services standing by.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, say souls on board and fuel remaining.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, roger on ground, remain on runway if required, assistance inbound."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, mayday, pedal failure, unable hover, requesting Congonhas run-on.",
      "ANAC123, Congonhas runway one seven left, wind copied.",
      "ANAC123, cleared to land one seven left, run-on landing.",
      "ANAC123, souls four, fuel one hour.",
      "ANAC123, on ground, remaining on runway, request assistance."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Continuing to a rooftop pad after losing yaw control.  \n  ✔ Divert to a runway or large area; state unable hover.\n\n- ❌ Saying only \"problema no pedal\" without the limitation.  \n  ✔ Pedal failure, unable hover, request run-on landing.\n\n- ❌ Ignoring wind in the request.  \n  ✔ Ask for wind; it directly affects remaining yaw control.\n\n- ❌ Using pan-pan for complete loss of yaw control near the ground.  \n  ✔ Mayday when control for landing is threatened.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** Pedal Failure, Unable Hover, Request Run-On Landing\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, PED-l FAYL-yer, un-AY-bul HUV-er, reh-KWEST RUN-on LAN-ding\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Pedal → PED-l\n- Unable → un-AY-bul\n- Hover → HUV-er\n- Run-on → RUN-on\n\nPractice:\n\nUnable hover... request run-on landing.\n\nTogether:\n\nMayday, pedal failure, unable hover, requesting run-on landing Congonhas.",
