    "category": "Aircraft Systems",
    "meaningEn": "Fuel Filter Bypass is a system indication that differential pressure across the fuel filter has opened a bypass path, allowing fuel to continue to the engine while bypassing the clogged filter element.",
    "meaningPt": "Bypass do filtro de combustível.\n\nIndicação de que a pressão diferencial no filtro de combustível abriu um caminho de bypass, permitindo que o combustível continue ao motor contornando o elemento filtrante obstruído.",
    "whenUsed": "When fuel filter bypass illuminates, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger Pan Pan, fuel filter bypass acknowledged, say souls on board.",
    "sayPhrase": "Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, fuel filter bypass, reducing power, request priority landing Curitiba.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Fuel filter bypass illuminates in cruise with stable engine parameters. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, fuel filter bypass caution, engine stable, reducing power, request priority landing at nearest suitable airport. I would provide souls on board and fuel remaining when requested, and upgrade to Mayday if power becomes unstable.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Fuel Filter Bypass — an indication that the fuel filter is clogged and fuel is being routed around the filter element to keep the engine supplied.\n\nBypass protects continuous fuel flow, but it also means unfiltered fuel may reach the engine. Contaminants that clogged the filter can still threaten nozzles, pumps, and combustion stability.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations, a fuel filter bypass caution is a clear signal to reduce demand, land as soon as practicable, and communicate with ATC using standard urgency phraseology.\n\nUnderstanding how to report fuel filter bypass in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Fuel filter bypass means the filter has done its job — and is now full of what you do not want in the engine.\n\nThe bypass valve keeps fuel flowing. That buys time. It does not buy complacency.\n\nOn the H130, reduce power, protect remaining engine life, and land. Do not stretch the flight to a preferred base if a suitable site is closer.\n\nLink the indication to contamination: water, sediment, or microbial growth often precede bypass. After landing, maintenance must inspect the filter and sample the fuel before the next flight.\n\nCommunicate clearly. ATC needs the system name, your status, and your intention — not a long technical lecture on frequency.",
    "operationalContext": "You are in cruise at one thousand eight hundred feet in your H130 from Curitiba toward São José dos Pinhais.\n\nThe fuel filter bypass caution illuminates. Engine parameters remain within limits. You reduce collective and plan a precautionary landing.\n\nYou transmit Pan Pan, report fuel filter bypass, and request vectors to the nearest suitable airport. Approach provides priority routing. You land, shut down, and request filter inspection and fuel sampling.",
    "sayItCoach": "Fuel filter bypass, reducing power, request priority landing.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, fuel filter bypass caution, engine stable, reducing power, request priority landing at nearest suitable airport. I would provide souls on board and fuel remaining when requested, and upgrade to Mayday if power becomes unstable.",
    "memoryTrick": "**BYPASS** — **B**ypass keeps flow, **Y**ou still land soon, **P**an Pan if stable, **A**ssess engine trends, **S**ample fuel after shutdown, **S**top the mission.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When fuel filter bypass illuminates, the pilot should:\n\nFuel filter bypass reporting commonly includes:",
