    "displayTerm": "Tail Rotor Drive Failure",
    "term": "tail rotor drive failure",
    "slug": "tail-rotor-drive-failure",
    "category": "Helicopter Operations",
    "meaningEn": "Tail Rotor Drive Failure is a mechanical failure of the drive system that powers the tail rotor, causing loss or severe reduction of anti-torque thrust and directional control.",
    "meaningPt": "Falha do acionamento do rotor de cauda.\n\nFalha mecânica do sistema que aciona o rotor de cauda, causando perda ou redução severa do empuxo antitorque e do controle direcional.",
    "whenUsed": "When tail rotor drive fails, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger Mayday, tail rotor drive failure, say position and souls on board.",
    "sayPhrase": "Mayday Mayday Mayday, Approach, ANAC123, tail rotor drive failure, emergency landing ahead.",
    "icaoQuestion": "You lose tail rotor drive in cruise and establish a controllable emergency descent. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Mayday Mayday Mayday, Approach, tail rotor drive failure, emergency landing three miles east of Santos, souls on board four. I would fly the procedure first and transmit as soon as control allows.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Tail Rotor Drive Failure — complete or partial loss of drive to the tail rotor, resulting in loss of anti-torque control and potentially violent uncommanded yaw.\n\nThis is not LTE. LTE is insufficient thrust in certain conditions. Tail rotor drive failure is a mechanical loss of the anti-torque system itself.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations, recognition must be immediate: enter the appropriate emergency procedure, establish a controllable flight path or autorotation as required, and declare Mayday without delay.\n\nUnderstanding how to report tail rotor drive failure in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Tail rotor drive failure is one of the most demanding helicopter emergencies.\n\nYou lose the ability to cancel main rotor torque with pedals. The aircraft will yaw. Your response depends on airspeed and altitude — and it must match the AFM, not improvisation.\n\nOn the H130, know the procedure cold for hover, transition, and cruise. Reduce torque. Use airspeed and collective as the procedure directs. Aim for a suitable surface for a run-on landing when that is the published technique.\n\nDo not confuse this with LTE. LTE may recover with pedal and airspeed. Drive failure will not restore pedal authority.\n\nCommunicate Mayday when control actions allow. ATC needs position and the nature of the failure so rescue goes to the right place.",
    "operationalContext": "You are in cruise at one thousand five hundred feet in your H130 approaching the coast near Santos.\n\nA loud noise is followed by sudden right yaw. Pedals are ineffective. You reduce throttle and collective per procedure, establish a controllable descent toward an open field, and transmit Mayday when able.\n\nApproach clears the frequency and traffic. You complete an emergency run-on landing into wind as published for the failure mode, shut down, and report on the ground.",
    "sayItCoach": "Tail rotor drive failure, emergency landing ahead.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Mayday Mayday Mayday, Approach, tail rotor drive failure, emergency landing three miles east of Santos, souls on board four. I would fly the procedure first and transmit as soon as control allows.",
    "memoryTrick": "**DRIVE** — **D**etect yaw and dead pedals, **R**educe torque per AFM, **I**dentify landing area, **V**oice Mayday when able, **E**xecute run-on or autorotation landing.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When tail rotor drive fails, the pilot should:\n\nTail rotor drive failure reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger Mayday, tail rotor drive failure, say position and souls on board.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, all traffic clear, wind two two zero at one zero, land at your discretion.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, emergency services rolling to your reported field.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, confirm landing site and cancel Mayday when able.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, wind information two three zero at one two, report on ground."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "Mayday Mayday Mayday, Approach, ANAC123, tail rotor drive failure, emergency landing ahead.",
      "Mayday Mayday Mayday, ANAC123, loss of anti-torque, entering autorotation, landing open field.",
      "ANAC123, Mayday, tail rotor failure, souls on board four, three miles east of Santos.",
      "ANAC123, landing at my discretion, request fire services to the field.",
      "Approach, ANAC123, on the ground, Mayday cancelled, aircraft intact, request assistance."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Transmitting a long explanation before flying the emergency procedure.  \n  ✔ Aviate first; Mayday when able.\n\n- ❌ Calling the event LTE when pedals are completely ineffective after a mechanical bang.  \n  ✔ Report tail rotor drive failure or loss of anti-torque.\n\n- ❌ Trying to hover to a spot landing against the procedure.  \n  ✔ Follow the AFM technique for the failure and flight regime.\n\n- ❌ Forgetting to report on the ground so rescue can stand down or proceed.  \n  ✔ Report on the ground and cancel or update Mayday.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** Tail Rotor Drive Failure, Emergency Landing\n\n**Pronunciation:** TAYL ROH-ter DRYV FAYL-yur, ee-MER-jen-see LAN-ding\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Tail → TAYL\n- Rotor → ROH-ter (stress on first)\n- Failure → FAYL-yur (stress on first)\n- Emergency → ee-MER-jen-see (stress on second)\n\nPractice:\n\nTail rotor drive failure... emergency landing.\n\nTogether:\n\nTail rotor drive failure, emergency landing ahead.",
