    "category": "Helicopter Operations",
    "meaningEn": "AFCS Failure is the loss of automatic flight control system functions — such as autopilot, attitude retention, or stability augmentation — requiring the pilot to fly the helicopter fully manually without automated stabilization or coupled guidance.",
    "meaningPt": "Falha do AFCS (sistema automático de controle de voo).\n\nPerda das funções do sistema automático de controle de voo — como piloto automático, retenção de atitude ou aumento de estabilidade — exigindo que o piloto voe o helicóptero manualmente, sem estabilização automatizada ou guiamento acoplado.",
    "whenUsed": "When AFCS fails, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger AFCS failure, fly heading one eight zero, vectors ILS runway one four.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, AFCS failure, manual flight, request vectors ILS runway one four.",
    "icaoQuestion": "AFCS fails in IMC on vectors to an approach. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Approach, AFCS failure, manual flight, request continued vectors for ILS and minimal heading changes. If workload becomes unsafe I would declare: Pan Pan Pan Pan, AFCS failure, request diversion to VMC.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers AFCS Failure — loss of the Automatic Flight Control System, including autopilot, stability augmentation, or coupled modes that normally reduce pilot workload in the H130.\n\nWhen AFCS fails, the aircraft remains flyable, but the pilot must assume full manual stabilization. Workload rises sharply in IMC, turbulence, or during instrument approaches.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations, AFCS failure requires an immediate transition to manual flight, a reassessment of weather and approach capability, and clear communication with ATC if you need vectors, a simpler approach, or a diversion.\n\nUnderstanding how to report AFCS failure in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "AFCS is a workload reducer — not a substitute for hand-flying skill.\n\nWhen it fails, your first job is attitude. Trim and stabilize. Then decide: can you safely continue this approach manually in these conditions?\n\nOn the H130, daylight VMC AFCS failure may be a maintenance diversion after a normal landing. Night IMC in turbulence may be Pan Pan and a request for the simplest path to VMC.\n\nTell ATC what you need: vectors, no complex SID/STAR gymnastics, or diversion. Do not silently accept a workload you cannot manage.\n\nNever chase coupled modes that are clearly failed. Confirm disconnect. Fly the aircraft.",
    "operationalContext": "You are in IMC at flight level seven zero in your H130 toward Florianópolis with AFCS coupled.\n\nAFCS fails. The helicopter pitches and rolls slightly before you take manual control and stabilize. Workload is high in cloud.\n\nYou advise Approach of AFCS failure, request radar vectors for the ILS, and ask for no speed or heading changes without notice. If conditions exceed comfortable manual IMC capability, you declare Pan Pan and request diversion to VMC.",
    "sayItCoach": "AFCS failure, manual flight, request radar vectors.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Approach, AFCS failure, manual flight, request continued vectors for ILS and minimal heading changes. If workload becomes unsafe I would declare: Pan Pan Pan Pan, AFCS failure, request diversion to VMC.",
    "memoryTrick": "**AFCS** — **A**ttitude first manually, **F**lag the failure to ATC, **C**hoose simpler approach or divert, **S**top chasing dead coupled modes.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When AFCS fails, the pilot should:\n\nAFCS failure reporting commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger AFCS failure, fly heading one eight zero, vectors ILS runway one four.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, roger Pan Pan, divert approved, turn left heading zero nine zero.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, maintain three thousand, expect ILS approach.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, runway one four cleared to land, wind one five zero at one two.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, say intentions and fuel remaining."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, AFCS failure, manual flight, request vectors ILS runway one four.",
      "Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, AFCS failure, high workload in IMC, request diversion.",
      "ANAC123, heading one eight zero, vectors ILS one four.",
      "ANAC123, Pan Pan, AFCS failed, souls on board three, request priority vectors.",
      "Tower, ANAC123, cleared to land runway one four, AFCS inoperative."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Saying nothing and accepting a complex clearance after AFCS fails.  \n  ✔ Advise AFCS failure and request vectors or simplification.\n\n- ❌ Declaring Mayday for a daytime VMC AFCS failure with full control.  \n  ✔ Mayday is for distress; use Pan Pan when conditions make manual flight urgent.\n\n- ❌ Attempting to re-engage failed modes repeatedly in IMC.  \n  ✔ Fly manually; troubleshoot only when stable and appropriate.\n\n- ❌ Forgetting to reassess approach minima and personal limits.  \n  ✔ Manual IMC has higher workload — divert if required.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** AFCS Failure, Request Radar Vectors\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-eff-SEE-ess FAYL-yur, reh-KWEST RAY-dar VEK-terz\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- AFCS → AY-eff-SEE-ess (spell it clearly)\n- Failure → FAYL-yur\n- Radar → RAY-dar\n- Vectors → VEK-terz\n\nPractice:\n\nAFCS failure... request radar vectors.\n\nTogether:\n\nAFCS failure, manual flight, request radar vectors.",
