    "category": "Helicopter Operations",
    "meaningEn": "Engine Overtorque is a condition in which measured torque exceeds the maximum permitted limit for the engine or transmission, risking mechanical damage to the powertrain.",
    "meaningPt": "Sobretorque do motor (overtorque).\n\nCondição em que o torque medido excede o limite máximo permitido para o motor ou a transmissão, com risco de dano mecânico ao conjunto de potência.",
    "whenUsed": "When engine overtorque occurs, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, roger Pan Pan, engine overtorque, say souls on board and intentions.",
    "sayPhrase": "Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, ANAC123, engine overtorque, reducing power, request priority landing São José.",
    "icaoQuestion": "You overtorque on departure, then torque returns to normal with no vibration. What do you say?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, engine overtorque on departure, torque now normal, request priority landing nearest suitable for inspection. I would state souls on board when asked and upgrade to Mayday if abnormal indications appear.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Engine Overtorque — torque exceeding published engine or transmission limits, indicating the powertrain is being loaded beyond design limits for the condition.\n\nOvertorque stresses the engine, main gearbox, and drive train. Transient exceedances may require inspection; sustained or severe overtorque can lead to failure.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations, the response is immediate: reduce collective to bring torque within limits, assess severity, land as required by the AFM, and communicate with ATC using the appropriate urgency.\n\nUnderstanding how to report engine overtorque in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 2 and Part 3 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Torque is the load on the entire drive train.\n\nWhen you overtorque, you may have already marked the gearbox and engine for inspection — even if everything feels normal afterward.\n\nOn the H130, reduce collective smoothly. Do not slam the power off and create a second problem with Nr. Once within limits, decide: how severe was the exceedance? The AFM and maintenance criteria drive whether you land ASAP or continue briefly to a suitable site.\n\nCommunicate. Pan Pan gets you priority without pretending the event was nothing. If vibration, noise, or pressure abnormalities follow — Mayday.\n\nNever hide an overtorque from maintenance. The next crew inherits what you do not write down.",
    "operationalContext": "You are departing a confined area near the Serra do Mar in your H130.\n\nTorque spikes above the limit during the departure. You reduce collective as soon as clear of obstacles, and torque returns to the green. You note the peak reading.\n\nYou declare Pan Pan, report engine overtorque, and request priority landing at the nearest suitable airport for inspection. Approach provides routing. You land with conservative power and report the exceedance to maintenance.",
    "sayItCoach": "Engine overtorque, reducing power, request priority landing.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Pan Pan Pan Pan, Approach, engine overtorque on departure, torque now normal, request priority landing nearest suitable for inspection. I would state souls on board when asked and upgrade to Mayday if abnormal indications appear.",
    "memoryTrick": "**TORQUE** — **T**ake collective down smoothly, **O**bserve Nr and vibes, **R**eport Pan Pan, **Q**uit the mission for inspection, **U**pgrade to Mayday if failure signs, **E**nter the exceedance in the tech log.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When engine overtorque occurs, the pilot should:\n\nEngine overtorque reporting commonly includes:",
