    "catalogId": "0480",
    "id": "0480",
    "displayTerm": "Leans",
    "term": "leans",
    "slug": "leans",
    "category": "Human Factors",
    "meaningEn": "The Leans is a vestibular illusion in which the pilot experiences a false sensation of bank, typically after an unnoticed gradual roll or after leveling from a turn, and may apply control inputs that create an actual opposite bank.",
    "meaningPt": "The Leans / Ilusão de inclinação.\n\nIlusão vestibular em que o piloto experimenta uma falsa sensação de inclinação lateral, tipicamente após uma rolagem gradual não percebida ou após nivelar de uma curva, e pode aplicar comandos que criam uma inclinação real no sentido oposto.",
    "whenUsed": "When the leans are suspected, the crew should:",
    "example": "Radar: ANAC123, fly present heading, maintain four thousand.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, present heading, maintaining four thousand.",
    "icaoQuestion": "After leveling from an IMC turn you feel banked. Instruments show wings level. What do you do?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would hold wings level on the attitude indicator and refuse to correct the sensation. If needed I would request time: ANAC123, requesting straight ahead, stabilizing. I would accept further turns only when the instrument scan is solid and the false lean has reduced.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers the Leans — a common vestibular illusion in which a pilot incorrectly senses a bank attitude after a sub-threshold roll or after recovering from a turn, leading to inappropriate \"corrections\" into a real bank.\n\nThe leans are subtle. A slow roll goes unnoticed. When instruments show wings level, the pilot still feels banked and leans the other way — creating a genuine spiral risk in IMC.\n\nIn H130 instrument flight, prolonged vectors, holding, and gentle intercepts can all set up the leans. Recognition and instrument discipline prevent a quiet illusion from becoming an unusual attitude.\n\nUnderstanding how to manage the leans in ICAO-standard English — including requests for straight-and-level time and simple vectors — supports Part 1, Part 2, and Part 4 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "The leans are a quiet liar.\n\nNo drama. Just a persistent feeling that the world is tilted. Then a \"correction\" that tilts it for real.\n\nIn the H130, make wings-level a verbal confirmation in IMC: \"Level on instruments.\" Say it. Mean it. Hold it.\n\nIf the lean will not leave, ask ATC for straight flight. There is no prize for maneuvering while disoriented.",
    "operationalContext": "Holding in IMC near Porto Alegre. After rollout you feel right-wing-low. Instruments show level. You start to lift the right wing — and actually bank left.\n\nYour first officer says: \"Wings level — trust it.\"\n\nYou hold the attitude and call:\n\nANAC123, requesting straight ahead one minute, vestibular leans, stabilizing.\n\nRadar: ANAC123, fly present heading, maintain four thousand, report ready for turn.\n\nYou respond:\n\nANAC123, present heading, maintaining four thousand, will report ready.\n\nSensation fades. Scan stabilizes. Holding resumes.",
    "sayItCoach": "ANAC123, requesting straight ahead one minute, stabilizing.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would hold wings level on the attitude indicator and refuse to correct the sensation. If needed I would request time: ANAC123, requesting straight ahead, stabilizing. I would accept further turns only when the instrument scan is solid and the false lean has reduced.",
    "memoryTrick": "**LEAN** — **L**et the attitude indicator decide, **E**nd false corrections, **A**sk for straight flight if needed, **N**otify the other pilot of the sensation.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When the leans are suspected, the crew should:\n\nLeans prevention includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Radar: ANAC123, fly present heading, maintain four thousand.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, confirm wings level, left turn observed.",
      "Radar: ANAC123, gentle right turn heading three six zero.",
      "Control: ANAC123, continue straight ahead, report when ready.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, vectors to final when able, advise."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, present heading, maintaining four thousand.",
      "ANAC123, wings level on instruments, correcting.",
      "ANAC123, gentle right turn heading three six zero.",
      "ANAC123, continuing straight ahead, will report ready.",
      "ANAC123, ready for vectors to final."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Banking to cancel a false lean after rollout.  \n  ✔ Hold instrument wings-level until the sensation fades.\n\n- ❌ Staying silent while fighting the illusion through a hold.  \n  ✔ Request straight ahead if stabilization is required.\n\n- ❌ Making abrupt corrections when the lean returns.  \n  ✔ Use small, instrument-referenced inputs only.\n\n- ❌ Skipping a cross-check with the other pilot.  \n  ✔ Confirm bank state verbally before any \"correction.\"",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** ANAC123, Requesting Straight Ahead, Stabilizing\n\n**Pronunciation:** AY-nak WUN TOO THREE, reh-KWEST-ing STRAYT uh-HED, STAY-buh-lize-ing\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Requesting → reh-KWEST-ing\n- Straight → STRAYT\n- Ahead → uh-HED\n- Stabilizing → STAY-buh-lize-ing\n\nPractice:\n\nRequesting straight ahead... stabilizing.\n\nTogether:\n\nANAC123, requesting straight ahead one minute, stabilizing.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "Vestibular Illusion",
      "Somatogravic Illusion",
      "Spatial Disorientation",
      "Instrument Scan",
      "Holding Pattern",
      "Unusual Attitude Recovery"
    ],
