    "catalogId": "0486",
    "id": "0486",
    "displayTerm": "Just Culture",
    "term": "just culture",
    "slug": "just-culture",
    "category": "CRM",
    "meaningEn": "Just Culture is a safety management principle that encourages open reporting of errors, hazards, and near misses by protecting reporters from punitive action for honest mistakes, while holding individuals accountable for reckless behavior, intentional non-compliance, or actions that knowingly endanger flight safety.",
    "meaningPt": "Cultura justa / Just Culture.\n\nPrincípio de gestão da segurança que incentiva o relato aberto de erros, perigos e quase acidentes, protegendo quem reporta de punição por erros honestos, mas mantendo a responsabilização por conduta imprudente, não conformidade intencional ou ações que coloquem a segurança do voo em risco de forma consciente.",
    "whenUsed": "When applying Just Culture on the line, the crew should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, confirm heading two seven zero, previous readback incorrect.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, negative, say again heading, previous readback incorrect.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Explain what Just Culture means and how it affects how a pilot reports an honest operational error.?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Just Culture means the organization encourages open reporting of honest mistakes and near misses without unfair punishment, while still holding people accountable for willful violations. If I make an honest error — for example selecting the wrong frequency and correcting it — I would report the facts clearly, describe the recovery, and support any SMS follow-up. I would not hide the event. The goal is learning and hazard removal, not blame for normal human error.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Just Culture — an organizational safety climate in which people are encouraged to report errors and hazards without fear of unfair punishment, while still remaining accountable for willful misconduct or gross negligence.\n\nJust Culture is not a free pass. It separates honest human error from deliberate violations so that learning can happen and safety can improve.\n\nFor H130 helicopter operations under ICAO Delta training, Just Culture shapes how crews discuss mistakes after a flight, how they report near misses, and how they speak about safety events in Part 1 and Part 4 English without hiding the truth.\n\nUnderstanding Just Culture in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 1 proficiency and Part 4 operational discussion.",
    "captainTeaching": "Just Culture is courage with structure.\n\nIf you hide a mistake, the next crew inherits it. If you report an honest error, the system can fix the trap that caught you.\n\nIn the H130, many events never appear on the radio — a near wire strike in a confined area, a late go-around decision, a checklist item almost skipped. Those belong in the report system too.\n\nPart 1 examiners listen for balanced language: you describe the error, the recovery, and the learning. You do not dramatize, and you do not minimize.\n\nAccountability still exists. Flying drunk, ignoring a MEL, or lying on a report is not Just Culture. It is misconduct.",
    "operationalContext": "You are flying an H130 from Congonhas to Santos. On departure you select the wrong VHF frequency for a few seconds, then correct it before missing a call.\n\nIn a punitive culture you might stay silent. In a Just Culture you note the event, brief the other pilot, and file a short voluntary report after landing: wrong frequency selected, corrected immediately, no ATC contact missed.\n\nLater, Approach asks you to confirm a heading you misheard. You admit the error, request say again, and read back correctly. Honesty on frequency and honesty in the SMS report are the same habit.",
    "sayItCoach": "We file a voluntary safety report for an honest error under Just Culture.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Just Culture means the organization encourages open reporting of honest mistakes and near misses without unfair punishment, while still holding people accountable for willful violations. If I make an honest error — for example selecting the wrong frequency and correcting it — I would report the facts clearly, describe the recovery, and support any SMS follow-up. I would not hide the event. The goal is learning and hazard removal, not blame for normal human error.",
    "memoryTrick": "**JUST** — **J**udge the act (error vs violation), **U**ncover the facts without fear, **S**hare the report promptly, **T**rain the system from the lesson.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When applying Just Culture on the line, the crew should:\n\nJust Culture discussions commonly include:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Approach: ANAC123, confirm heading two seven zero, previous readback incorrect.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, say again intentions, last transmission unclear.",
      "Control: ANAC123, report if unable to comply, no penalty for early advice.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, traffic conflict resolved, request pilot report if desired.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, confirm parking stand, previous call copied incorrectly."
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, negative, say again heading, previous readback incorrect.",
      "ANAC123, request say again intentions, last call unclear.",
      "ANAC123, unable to comply as cleared, request alternative.",
      "ANAC123, wilco, will file safety report after landing if required.",
      "ANAC123, parking stand confirmed, previous call corrected."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Treating Just Culture as “no consequences for anything.”  \n  ✔ Honest errors are protected; reckless or intentional violations are not.\n\n- ❌ Hiding near misses because “nothing happened.”  \n  ✔ Near misses are the best learning data — report them.\n\n- ❌ Writing emotional or vague reports instead of facts.  \n  ✔ State what, when, where, and how you recovered — clearly in English.\n\n- ❌ Blaming ATC or the other pilot to avoid self-reporting.  \n  ✔ Report your own actions factually; systems learn from truth.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** Voluntary Safety Report, Honest Error, No Unfair Punishment\n\n**Pronunciation:** VOL-uhn-teh-ree SAYF-tee rih-PORT, ON-ist EHR-or, noh un-FAIR PUN-ish-ment\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Voluntary → VOL-uhn-teh-ree (stress on first)\n- Safety → SAYF-tee\n- Report → rih-PORT (stress on second)\n- Honest → ON-ist\n\nPractice:\n\nVoluntary safety report... honest error... Just Culture.\n\nTogether:\n\nWe file a voluntary safety report for an honest error under Just Culture.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "Safety Culture",
      "Hazard Identification",
      "Risk Assessment",
      "Debriefing",
      "Crew Resource Management",
      "Safety Management System"
    ],
    "references": [
      {
        "label": "ICAO Doc 9859 — Safety Management Manual (Just Culture)"
      },
      {
        "label": "ICAO Annex 19 — Safety Management"
      },
      {
        "label": "SKYbrary — Just Culture",
        "href": "https://skybrary.aero"
      },
      {
        "label": "EASA / ICAO guidance on occurrence reporting"
      },
      {
        "label": "DECEA / Brazilian SMS reporting frameworks"
      },
      {
        "label": "H130 AFM — Operational Safety Practices"
      }
    ]
