    "displayTerm": "Hazard Identification",
    "term": "hazard identification",
    "slug": "hazard-identification",
    "category": "CRM",
    "meaningEn": "Hazard Identification is the process of recognizing and describing any condition, object, activity, or event with the potential to cause injury, damage, or loss of control, so that risk assessment and mitigation can follow before the hazard becomes an occurrence.",
    "meaningPt": "Identificação de perigos / Hazard Identification.\n\nProcesso de reconhecer e descrever qualquer condição, objeto, atividade ou evento com potencial de causar lesão, dano ou perda de controle, para que a avaliação e a mitigação de risco possam ocorrer antes que o perigo se torne uma ocorrência.",
    "whenUsed": "When identifying hazards, the crew should:",
    "example": "Tower: ANAC123, report intentions.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, going around, wires on approach path.",
    "icaoQuestion": "What is hazard identification and how does it help flight safety?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Hazard identification means recognizing and clearly describing anything that could cause harm — for example wires, weather, fatigue, or an unclear clearance — so the crew can assess risk and apply mitigations. It improves safety because unspoken hazards cannot be managed, briefed, or reported to protect the next flight.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Hazard Identification — the CRM and SMS skill of recognizing conditions, objects, or events that can cause harm before they become an incident.\n\nYou cannot manage a risk you never named. Hazard identification is the first link in the safety chain: see it, say it, then assess it.\n\nFor H130 operations, hazards are often visual and immediate — wires, masts, deck motion, brownout — but also systemic: fatigue, rushed briefings, unclear clearances. Part 1, Part 2, and Part 4 English must name hazards precisely.\n\nUnderstanding hazard identification in ICAO-standard English is essential across Parts 1, 2, and 4.",
    "captainTeaching": "Hazard identification is seeing plus saying.\n\nTEM starts with threats. If the threat stays in your head, the other pilot cannot help you.\n\nIn Part 1 answers, name hazards specifically: wire across final, gusty crosswind, high density altitude — not “bad conditions.”\n\nIn the H130, the crewman is often your best hazard sensor near the pad. Brief that obstacle calls are welcome and mandatory.\n\nSome hazards belong on the radio immediately — debris, animals, wire discoveries that affect the next aircraft. That is safety citizenship, not drama.",
    "operationalContext": "You are approaching a private helipad outside Campinas in the H130. On short final the crewman calls wires on the approach path — previously unmarked on your mental map.\n\nYou discontinue the approach, climb away, and advise Tower you are unable to land, repositioning for a different path. The hazard was identified, spoken, and acted on. After landing you file a hazard report so the next crew is not surprised.",
    "sayItCoach": "Going around, wires on approach path, requesting reposition.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Hazard identification means recognizing and clearly describing anything that could cause harm — for example wires, weather, fatigue, or an unclear clearance — so the crew can assess risk and apply mitigations. It improves safety because unspoken hazards cannot be managed, briefed, or reported to protect the next flight.",
    "memoryTrick": "**HAZARD** — **H**unt with eyes and ears, **A**nnounce it out loud, **Z**ero delay on critical calls, **A**ssess the risk next, **R**educe or reject, **D**ocument recurring traps.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When identifying hazards, the crew should:\n\nHazard identification commonly includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Tower: ANAC123, report intentions.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, confirm go-around, advise reason if able.",
      "Approach: ANAC123, hold present position, traffic.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, report if any aerodrome hazard observed.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, cleared to reposition, report final."
    ],
