    "category": "ICAO Speaking",
    "meaningEn": "Structure is the ICAO language proficiency skill that assesses control of grammatical forms and sentence patterns — from simple clauses to more complex constructions — so that operational meaning remains clear, coherent, and unambiguous in speech.",
    "meaningPt": "Estrutura / Structure.\n\nHabilidade de proficiência linguística da OACI que avalia o controle de formas gramaticais e padrões de frase — de orações simples a construções mais complexas — para que o significado operacional permaneça claro, coerente e inequívoco na fala.",
    "whenUsed": "When demonstrating structure, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, advise intentions if weather deteriorates.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, if weather deteriorates, diverting Congonhas.",
    "icaoQuestion": "Why is structure important in ICAO Aviation English, and how can you show it in a Part 1 answer?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Structure keeps meaning clear by controlling grammar and sentence order. In a Part 1 answer I use a clear pattern such as PEEL — point, explain, example, link — with simple accurate sentences and connectors. Even if I make small errors, the listener can follow my decision and my reasons without confusion.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Structure — the ICAO language skill that evaluates how well you control basic and complex grammatical patterns so that meaning stays clear in operational speaking and radiotelephony plain language.\n\nStructure is the skeleton of your message. Weak structure forces the listener to rebuild your meaning. Strong structure lets ATC and examiners follow you on the first pass.\n\nFor H130 ICAO Delta Part 1 answers, PEEL organization plus clean grammar turns knowledge into Level 4 performance.\n\nUnderstanding structure as an ICAO skill is essential for Part 1 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Structure is how professionals think out loud.\n\nPEEL is not a school trick. It is how you keep a long answer from collapsing.\n\nOn frequency, structure is shorter: intention + reason if needed + request. Do not narrate your entire mental model to ATC.\n\nBrazilian speakers often front the topic and delay the verb. In English aviation speech, put the action early: diverting, requesting, unable, going around.\n\nIn the H130, sequence language matters for emergencies: first enter autorotation, then mayday, then landing area. Structure saves order when stress steals memory.",
    "operationalContext": "An examiner asks what you would do if weather drops below minima on an H130 approach to Santos.\n\nAn unstructured answer jumps between fuel, passengers, and feelings. A structured answer uses PEEL: Point — I would discontinue and divert. Explain — because minima are not available and fuel allows Congonhas. Example — I would request diversion routing. Link — that keeps the operation inside company and ICAO safety standards.\n\nOn frequency the same structure becomes: unable to continue approach, diverting Congonhas, request routing.",
    "sayItCoach": "Weather below minima, diverting Congonhas, request routing.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Structure keeps meaning clear by controlling grammar and sentence order. In a Part 1 answer I use a clear pattern such as PEEL — point, explain, example, link — with simple accurate sentences and connectors. Even if I make small errors, the listener can follow my decision and my reasons without confusion.",
    "memoryTrick": "**PEEL** — **P**oint first, **E**xplain why, **E**xample from operations, **L**ink back to safety or procedure.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When demonstrating structure, the pilot should:\n\nStructure in practice commonly includes:",
