    "meaningEn": "Vocabulary is the ICAO language proficiency skill that evaluates the breadth and accuracy of words and phrases a speaker can use and paraphrase to communicate effectively on familiar and unfamiliar aeronautical topics in both phraseology and plain language.",
    "meaningPt": "Vocabulário / Vocabulary.\n\nHabilidade de proficiência linguística da OACI que avalia a amplitude e a precisão das palavras e expressões que o falante consegue usar e parafrasear para comunicar-se com eficácia em tópicos aeronáuticos familiares e não familiares, tanto em fraseologia quanto em linguagem clara.",
    "whenUsed": "When demonstrating vocabulary, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, confirm nature of problem.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, burning odour in cabin, no visible fire, request priority landing.",
    "icaoQuestion": "How can a pilot manage vocabulary limitations during an ICAO English test or on frequency?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I use standard phraseology when it fits, and precise plain language for abnormals. If I cannot recall a rare term, I paraphrase clearly instead of stopping. For example, I can describe fumes without visible fire and request priority landing. The goal is accurate meaning, not perfect wording.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Vocabulary — the ICAO language skill that measures whether you have enough words and paraphrases to discuss common and uncommon operational topics clearly, including when standard phraseology is not enough.\n\nVocabulary is range plus precision. You need the right aviation term when it exists, and a plain-language paraphrase when the exact word does not come.\n\nFor H130 ICAO Delta candidates, helicopter-specific vocabulary — hover, sling, winch, confined area — must sit beside core IFR and emergency lexicon for Part 1 success.\n\nUnderstanding vocabulary as an ICAO skill is essential for Part 1 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Vocabulary is the right tool, not the longest word.\n\nExaminers listen for precision: divert is not the same as delay; fumes are not the same as fire; unable is not the same as standby.\n\nWhen the exact term disappears under stress, paraphrase immediately: “the system that controls the rotor speed” is better than silence while you hunt for a memory.\n\nIn the H130, build a personal lexicon for external load, EMS, and deck work. Part 1 topics love helicopter specificity — reward it with accurate words.",
    "operationalContext": "In Part 1 you must describe an H130 with a burning smell in the cabin but no visible flames.\n\nWeak vocabulary says “problem with smoke maybe fire.” Strong vocabulary distinguishes: burning odour, no visible smoke, no confirmed fire, requesting priority landing and emergency services as a precaution.\n\nOn frequency that precision changes the response. Vocabulary is operational, not academic.",
    "sayItCoach": "Burning odour in cabin, no visible fire, request priority landing.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I use standard phraseology when it fits, and precise plain language for abnormals. If I cannot recall a rare term, I paraphrase clearly instead of stopping. For example, I can describe fumes without visible fire and request priority landing. The goal is accurate meaning, not perfect wording.",
    "memoryTrick": "**WORD** — **W**ord from phraseology first, **O**ffer a paraphrase if stuck, **R**efine precision (fumes vs fire), **D**eliver the request to ATC.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When demonstrating vocabulary, the pilot should:\n\nVocabulary work commonly includes:",
