    "slug": "fluency",
    "category": "ICAO Speaking",
    "meaningEn": "Fluency is the ICAO language proficiency skill that assesses the ability to speak at an appropriate tempo with natural phrasing and limited disruption from hesitation, so that aeronautical messages remain continuous, understandable, and professionally paced.",
    "meaningPt": "Fluência / Fluency.\n\nHabilidade de proficiência linguística da OACI que avalia a capacidade de falar em ritmo apropriado, com fraseado natural e pouca interrupção por hesitações, de modo que as mensagens aeronáuticas permaneçam contínuas, compreensíveis e com ritmo profissional.",
    "whenUsed": "When demonstrating fluency, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, advise intentions.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, requesting vectors for second approach.",
    "icaoQuestion": "What is fluency in ICAO Aviation English, and how do you maintain it under pressure?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "Fluency means speaking at an appropriate pace with natural flow and limited hesitation so the listener can follow continuously. Under pressure I use short clear sentences and sequencing words like first and then, and if I get stuck I simplify instead of stopping. Fluency is smooth communication, not speaking as fast as possible.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Fluency — the ICAO language skill that evaluates how smoothly and naturally you produce speech, including appropriate rate, pausing, and the ability to keep talking without excessive hesitation or memorized-sounding fragments.\n\nFluency is not speed. A rushed pilot can be disfluent. A calm pilot with natural pauses can score well. Level 4 fluency means you can keep the message moving through an operational topic.\n\nFor H130 ICAO Delta Part 1 candidates, fluency shows when you describe a sequence — approach, decision, go-around — without long silent searches or constant restarts.\n\nUnderstanding fluency as an ICAO skill is essential for Part 1 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Fluency is continuity with control.\n\nSpeed is a false friend. Many Brazilian candidates rush, then crash into a vocabulary hole and stop. Better: moderate rate, short sentences, keep moving.\n\nUse scaffolding phrases: first, then, after that, finally. They create fluency while your brain selects content.\n\nIn the H130, rehearse the mayday and pan sequences until they are smooth. Fluency under adrenaline is a trained motor skill, not a personality trait.\n\nOn frequency, release the push-to-talk only when the thought is ready — then speak once.",
    "operationalContext": "In a mock oral you are asked to explain a rejected landing in the H130. You start, stop, restart, and apologize in Portuguese in your head for ten seconds of silence.\n\nThat silence is a fluency break. Instead you use a bridge: “First I would... then I would... finally I would advise ATC.” The connectors buy thinking time without empty air.\n\nOn frequency the same habit produces one clean call: going around, requesting vectors for second approach — not three broken attempts.",
    "sayItCoach": "",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "Fluency means speaking at an appropriate pace with natural flow and limited hesitation so the listener can follow continuously. Under pressure I use short clear sentences and sequencing words like first and then, and if I get stuck I simplify instead of stopping. Fluency is smooth communication, not speaking as fast as possible.",
    "memoryTrick": "**FLOW** — **F**irst/then connectors ready, **L**ower speed to stay clear, **O**ffer a simpler sentence if stuck, **W**in continuity — keep talking productively.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When demonstrating fluency, the pilot should:\n\nFluency practice commonly includes:",
