    "slug": "comprehension",
    "category": "ICAO Speaking",
    "meaningEn": "Comprehension is the ICAO language proficiency skill that evaluates a listener’s ability to understand spoken aeronautical English — including routine and non-routine messages, varied accents, and imperfect conditions — and to recognize when clarification is required before acting.",
    "meaningPt": "Compreensão / Comprehension.\n\nHabilidade de proficiência linguística da OACI que avalia a capacidade do ouvinte de entender inglês aeronáutico falado — incluindo mensagens de rotina e não rotina, sotaques variados e condições imperfeitas — e de reconhecer quando é necessário esclarecimento antes de agir.",
    "whenUsed": "When demonstrating comprehension, the pilot should:",
    "example": "Approach: ANAC123, descend two thousand, turn left heading one two zero.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, say again altitude, heading one two zero copied.",
    "icaoQuestion": "What should you do if you do not fully understand an ATC clearance or an examiner question?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I should not guess. I should request clarification — for example say again, or confirm the missed element — and then read back or answer only what I have understood. Comprehension includes recognizing misunderstanding and repairing it before I act or continue speaking.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Comprehension — the ICAO language skill that measures how accurately you understand spoken English in radiotelephony and operational interaction, including accents, unexpected turns, and less ideal audio conditions.\n\nComprehension is the quiet skill that saves flights. If you misunderstand a clearance, perfect pronunciation on the wrong readback still fails. Level 4 requires understanding common work-related topics and the ability to clarify when something is missed.\n\nFor H130 ICAO Delta Part 1 candidates, comprehension includes following examiner questions, ATC-style prompts, and unexpected follow-ups without guessing.\n\nUnderstanding comprehension as an ICAO skill is essential for Part 1 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Comprehension is humility on frequency.\n\nThe dangerous pilot is not the one who says say again. The dangerous pilot is the one who fills silence with a guessed number.\n\nTrain your ear with real ATC recordings, different accents, and overlapping calls. Part 1 examiners also change direction mid-question — listen to the end.\n\nIn the H130, cabin noise and intercom clutter attack comprehension. Slow the cockpit, isolate the radio call, then answer. Understanding beats responding first.\n\nReadback is comprehension made visible. Use it.",
    "operationalContext": "Approach clears you to descend to two thousand and turn left heading one two zero. You hear the heading but miss the altitude under frequency noise.\n\nYou do not invent two thousand or three thousand. You call say again altitude. Approach repeats. You read back both elements.\n\nIn Part 1 the examiner asks a two-part question. You paraphrase: “If I understand correctly, you want the immediate action and then the radio call?” That check is comprehension skill — the same habit that keeps the H130 on the right altitude.",
    "sayItCoach": "Say again altitude, heading one two zero copied.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I should not guess. I should request clarification — for example say again, or confirm the missed element — and then read back or answer only what I have understood. Comprehension includes recognizing misunderstanding and repairing it before I act or continue speaking.",
    "memoryTrick": "**HEAR** — **H**alt guessing, **E**licit a repeat if needed, **A**cknowledge what you did copy, **R**ead back the full clearance before acting.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When demonstrating comprehension, the pilot should:\n\nComprehension strategies commonly include:",
