    "catalogId": "0502",
    "id": "0502",
    "displayTerm": "Describing a Picture",
    "term": "describing a picture",
    "slug": "describing-a-picture",
    "category": "ICAO Speaking",
    "meaningEn": "Describing a Picture is the ICAO speaking task type in which the candidate observes an aviation-related image and produces a coherent oral description — covering main elements, location, actions, and relevant context — so that vocabulary range, structure, and fluency can be assessed at Operational Level 4 or higher.",
    "meaningPt": "Descrição de uma imagem / Describing a Picture.\n\nTipo de tarefa oral da ICAO em que o candidato observa uma imagem relacionada à aviação e produz uma descrição oral coerente — cobrindo elementos principais, localização, ações e contexto relevante — para avaliar vocabulário, estrutura e fluência no Nível Operacional 4 ou superior.",
    "whenUsed": "When describing a picture, the candidate should:",
    "example": "Examiner: ANAC123, look at the picture and describe what you see.",
    "sayPhrase": "ANAC123, wilco — describing the picture now, helicopter on helipad in view.",
    "icaoQuestion": "The examiner shows a picture of an airport apron with a helicopter, a fuel truck, and ground crew. How do you organize a Level 4 description?",
    "icaoSpeakText": "I would start with the overall scene: This picture shows an airport apron. Then the main subject: There is a helicopter parked near the center. Then related elements: On the right there is a fuel truck, and ground crew are standing near the aircraft. Then conditions or actions: It looks like the helicopter is being prepared for departure. I would keep sentences short, use location words, and stop after a clear structure so the examiner can ask follow-ups.",
    "missionBrief": "Today's lesson covers Describing a Picture — the ICAO oral exam task in which you observe an aviation-related image and produce a clear, organized spoken description at Level 4 or above.\n\nDescribing a picture is not listing random objects. It is structured observation.\n\nIn Part 1, the examiner shows a photograph or drawing — often an airport scene, cockpit, weather event, or helicopter operation — and expects you to describe what you see, where things are, and what may be happening. Organization, vocabulary, and fluency matter more than artistic detail.\n\nFor H130 ICAO Delta candidates, picture description is a high-value Part 1 skill: it tests aviation vocabulary under time pressure without requiring memorized ATC scripts.\n\nUnderstanding how to describe a picture in ICAO-standard English is essential for Part 1 proficiency.",
    "captainTeaching": "Picture description rewards structure.\n\nCandidates who panic name five objects with no order. Examiners hear chaos. Candidates who open with the scene, then locate elements, then add one inference sound Level 4.\n\nUse a simple frame: What is this place? What is the main subject? Where are the other elements? What is happening? What might happen next — only if asked or if clearly suggested.\n\nVocabulary beats poetry. \"Helicopter on the helipad, marshaller on the left, hangar behind\" is better than searching for rare adjectives.\n\nIf you do not know a word, describe the function: \"the person who guides the aircraft on the ground\" instead of freezing on \"marshaller.\"\n\nIn H130 training you already brief visual scenes — landing sites, obstacles, wind indicators. Transfer that briefing habit to the exam picture.",
    "operationalContext": "The examiner places a photo on the table: an H130 on a helipad, a marshaller with wands, a hangar in the background, light rain on the pavement.\n\nYou begin: This picture shows a helicopter on a helipad. In the foreground there is a marshaller giving signals. Behind the aircraft I can see a hangar. The surface looks wet, so it may be raining.\n\nYou continue with rotor, doors, and possible boarding. You do not invent an emergency that is not in the image.\n\nThe examiner nods and asks one follow-up about wet-helipad operations. Your description created the bridge for interaction.",
    "sayItCoach": "In the foreground there is a marshaller giving signals to the helicopter.",
    "icaoModelAnswer": "I would start with the overall scene: This picture shows an airport apron. Then the main subject: There is a helicopter parked near the center. Then related elements: On the right there is a fuel truck, and ground crew are standing near the aircraft. Then conditions or actions: It looks like the helicopter is being prepared for departure. I would keep sentences short, use location words, and stop after a clear structure so the examiner can ask follow-ups.",
    "memoryTrick": "**PICTURE** — **P**lace first in one sentence, **I**dentify the main subject, **C**atalog left-right and near-far, **T**ell actions with present continuous, **U**se aviation words you know, **R**eserve speculation for the end, **E**nd cleanly for follow-ups.",
    "operationalMeaning": "When describing a picture, the candidate should:\n\nA Level 4 picture description typically includes:",
    "whyAtcUsesIt": [],
    "atcPhraseology": [
      "Examiner: ANAC123, look at the picture and describe what you see.",
      "Examiner: ANAC123, focus on the aircraft in the foreground and continue.",
      "Tower: ANAC123, confirm helipad in sight, report when ready for landing.",
      "Ground: ANAC123, marshaller is in position, follow signals to the pad.",
      "Examiner: ANAC123, what do you think is happening in this scene?"
    ],
    "pilotReadbacks": [
      "ANAC123, wilco — describing the picture now, helicopter on helipad in view.",
      "ANAC123, focusing on the aircraft in the foreground, continuing description.",
      "ANAC123, helipad in sight, will report ready for landing.",
      "ANAC123, following marshaller signals to the pad.",
      "ANAC123, it appears boarding is in progress, marshaller directing the aircraft."
    ],
    "brazilianMistakes": "- ❌ Listing objects with no spatial organization.  \n  ✔ Use foreground / background / left / right systematically.\n\n- ❌ Inventing a dramatic story not supported by the image.  \n  ✔ Describe visible facts first; mark speculation clearly.\n\n- ❌ Long silence while searching for perfect vocabulary.  \n  ✔ Paraphrase unknown words and keep speaking.\n\n- ❌ Describing only the aircraft and ignoring people or weather.  \n  ✔ Cover setting, subjects, actions, and conditions.",
    "pronunciationCoaching": "**Target Phrase:** In the Foreground There Is a Marshaller\n\n**Pronunciation:** in thuh FOR-ground thair iz uh MAR-shuh-ler\n\n**Word Stress**\n\n- Foreground → FOR-ground (stress on first)\n- There → thair\n- Marshaller → MAR-shuh-ler\n- Signals → SIG-nulz\n\nPractice:\n\nIn the foreground... there is a marshaller.\n\nTogether:\n\nIn the foreground there is a marshaller giving signals to the helicopter.",
    "relatedConcepts": [
      "Interactions",
      "Describing an Unusual Situation",
      "Giving Opinions",
      "Spatial Language",
      "Aviation Vocabulary",
      "Present Continuous for Actions"
    ],
